Republican strategy to resist Obama&#39;s re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center dismisses the latter as a myth, arguing that electoral fraud in the United States is rarer than lightning deaths.
In addition, Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, US states are responsible for organizing US federal elections.
That is why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 that make it harder to register or vote.
This phenomenon gained new momentum after the November 2010 elections, which brought the Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills were passed restricting the right to vote in 41 states.
New election laws require voters to show a photo ID and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period for early voting, abolish the right to vote on the day of voting, and remove the right to vote from citizens with a criminal record.
Prior to the 2006 election, no US state required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
In 2008, the US Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of a law passed in Indiana.
Republican authorities hastened to extend this practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they have initiated bills requiring voters to show photo ID in 34 states.
It is important to note that, unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card such as a health insurance card.
Indeed, 11% of American citizens, that is, 21 million people of voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by their state government agency.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
However, the cost of obtaining the required ID often exceeds one hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $35,000, 18% of citizens over 65, and 20% of voters 18 to 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that is not all.
Student voters believed to be voting for Democratic candidates are not allowed in several states to use a photo ID issued by their school.
But these same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mostly Republican, to vote on identification cards issued by these clubs.
Prior to 2004, no state required proof of US citizenship in order to vote.
The first such requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than ten states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are US citizens.
These measures are apparently aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
It is believed that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators initiated laws in 2011 to abolish voter registration on Election Day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those wishing to register.
This restriction did not pass without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the voter registration campaign helped to enroll some 10 million citizens.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 resulted in a 17% drop in new voter registration rates in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the early voting period.
For example, during the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of voters who voted early were African Americans, although the latter made up only 13% of the state&#39;s total voters.
The same thing happened with immigrants from Latin America.
Representing only 11% of voters, they made up 24% of citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, who, while forming 76% of voters, were only 46% of those who voted early.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters actively oppose laws that would restrict voter registration.
Several bills have been vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended by the intervention of the United States Attorney General.
This made it possible to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states have adopted laws requiring photo identification.
However, the new rules that have come into effect will certainly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Democrat critics decry the bias of the laws that have been passed, seeing them as clearly intended to influence the outcome of the 2012 election in key states.
The 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that pass these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed in the Electoral College to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Prostate cancer screening: test or not?
In fact, the PSA test sometimes gives erroneous results, false negatives, and sometimes false positives, which lead to useless medical intervention.
Men, who are so reluctant to undergo medical examination, have something to doubt even more.
Pass the test or not?
We asked the opinion of two experts.
In studies conducted in the United States, there have been numerous cases of infection among study groups, so the data obtained is difficult to interpret and it is difficult to make any clear recommendations.
Another study, this time from Europe, found different mortality rates between screened and non-screened patients.
This study also showed, after a 12-year follow-up, that the likelihood of metastases is 30-40% higher in those who are not screened.
Therefore, I would recommend getting tested at age 50, or at age 40 if one of the immediate family members had prostate cancer.
African-American men are also at increased risk.
The key is to make the right decision once the cancer is discovered.
Cancer can be either aggressive or indolent.
The patient needs to be explained the risk of his cancer, offering him options, not necessarily treating prostate cancer, which is not life-threatening in the long term, but making the choice, in these cases, in favor of active monitoring of the disease.
Today, many men diagnosed with cancer will not receive treatment because their cancer is not aggressive or life-threatening.
We will offer them active monitoring, and if the disease starts to progress, we will start treatment.
Increasingly, we are specifying the exact criteria for deciding who should or should not receive treatment.
Thus, I would still recommend taking the test.
But it&#39;s also important to consult with your doctor to determine whether or not you should take this test.
In collaboration with the International Association of Urology, Movember has created a tool to evaluate the pros and cons of taking a PSA test.
