The Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, reports that scientists might have discovered the Higgs boson caused quite a stir - and with good reason.
It is believed that this boson explains the mass of all particles in the universe, no less.
It is also the last particle predicted to exist by the Standard Model - our best, or at any rate &quot;least imperfect&quot; description of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not previously been experimentally detected.
But physicists are not yet completely sure that we are talking about the Higgs boson.
We know beyond a shadow of a doubt that we are dealing with a truly new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
In addition, new data presented this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seems to confirm this, although there are still not enough data to be completely sure.
Imagine, however, that we are talking about the Higgs boson, since the chances of being wrong seem minimal, and let&#39;s see what this means.
There is, in this world, one absolutely inevitable law, which says that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way around this rule, don&#39;t even try too hard, otherwise you will hurt yourself.
But although particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of a similar nature: the Pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same &quot;quantum state&quot; - this &quot;state&quot; is, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens called fermions, who prudently obey the Pauli principle.
In the other, the Bosons scurry around, a nefarious gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least for this principle, which means that they can easily be in the same place at the same time.
According to the (by the way, quite unusual) Particle Adventure website of the Berkeley Lab, these bosons are divided, in turn, into two groups: mesons, which we will not talk about here, and &quot;particles of force&quot;, through which the main forces of nature are distributed and to to which the Higgs boson belongs in some way.
These very bosons, it should be emphasized, are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you&#39;re able to read this chronicle, it&#39;s because of one incredibly commonplace boson: the photon, or &quot;particle of light,&quot; which is the &quot;courier&quot; of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a single particle that has an electrical charge accelerates or changes direction, it &quot;breaks&quot; the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this &quot;violation&quot; an electromagnetic wave (of light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing more than a photon - and, therefore, one of the &quot;force carrier&quot; bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, must be &quot;broken&quot;.
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, you need to reach very, very high energies, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be shaken by a very large stone.
That&#39;s why a huge particle accelerator is needed, like the one operated at CERN - the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring with a diameter of 27 km! - to achieve such huge energies.
The electromagnetic field analogy is also useful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with an electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, interact, others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never stick to a refrigerator by itself.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have mass, while others (like the photon, by the way) do not.
So what does all this research &quot;may bring&quot;, asks Ms. Plamondon?
In science, they are used to test the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and it also allows physicists to feel for discrepancies between observations and predictions of the SM.
In addition, some of them are passionately eager for such a discrepancy to be revealed, since the slightest discrepancy can open the door for &quot;new physics&quot; and plug some of the holes in the Model.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (oops!) or for dark matter, which forms about 80% of the universe (oops!).
But so far no such discrepancies have been found at CERN.
Consequences
The benefits of these studies to the daily life of the average person are harder to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that they are not.
Look: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research at Bell Labs could not even imagine what a revolution their work would cause.
They foresaw their applications in science, but nothing more.
Indeed, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous-wave laser (the previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that the laser was originally considered more like &quot; laboratory gadget.
Imagine...
And besides, an application can be found for the toolkit accompanying the study.
For example, the same Williard Boyle, during his optical research in 1969, developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although it was not at all its original purpose, now serves as the &quot;eye&quot; for all digital cameras in the world and earned the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This, of course, does not mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it only shows, in fact, that anything can be.
Palliative care is the best way to die... | &quot;Duty&quot;
The Commission for a Dignified Death in Quebec recently debated the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume shortly, while the draft law is being drafted.
However, much remains to be done in this critical area.
Duty tried to take a closer look.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Monteregie.
Prostate cancer, which was destroying him from the inside, gave him a two-year reprieve.
&quot;I was given five years, I lived seven,&quot; he says, between life and death, lying in bed at the Victor-Gadbois palliative care home in Beleuil, where he arrived the day before.
&quot;But it&#39;s always a shock, you can&#39;t prepare for it,&quot; he says.
The disease does its job: an incredible weakness that prevents you from going to the toilet on your own and even eating on your own.
Sitting at a table with a delicious lunch on it, he gives in and agrees to be helped to eat.
He cheers up, even manages to smile, talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicine, take him to the bath.
Courage in the face of ordinary death.
&quot;My biggest desire is to be cured of my diarrhea, it&#39;s humiliating,&quot; he admits.
A few hours later, the staff found a cure for this ailment.
&quot;During our lives we are taught that a man should urinate standing up,&quot; says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois shelter.
To regress to the state of a child is an unbearable humiliation for some.
&quot;It all depends on a person&#39;s ability&quot; to come to terms with decline, he says.
Because, according to many people involved in palliative care, important events happen in the midst of this decline.
The patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Asylum are all sick with cancer.
Forecasts give them a maximum of three months of life.
At this stage, the team of doctors and nurses no longer provides care called &quot;treatment&quot;.
Ms. A., aged 89, is most afraid of dying &quot;conscious from suffocation&quot;.
But the disease allowed me to recognize my children.
&quot;I have good kids,&quot; she adds.
&quot;I don&#39;t want anything else in my life,&quot; she says, before allowing her to put on a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting in the coming days for the last visit of her son, who arrived from Italy.
At the Victor-Gadbois shelter, with the help of a group of volunteers, body care and nutrition assistance is provided.
This is the palliative care that remains when nothing else can be done.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one place in palliative care for every 11,700 residents.
This is very little, considering that sooner or later we will all die.
Here life goes on in the best conditions possible, explains Dr. Christian Martel, one of the doctors at the shelter.
Be it physical, emotional or mental comfort.
For a dying person we will agree to provide brandy or Pepsi mouthwashes, whichever he asks for.
We no longer force diabetics to control their sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we brought beer to Mr. X, who died last night.
In the morning his son drank this beer at the feet of the deceased.
&quot;We help loved ones as well as patients,&quot; says Nathalie Savard, Director of Nursing.
At the Victor Gadbois, no day is the same.
Next to a 93-year-old man who is enjoying his last meeting with his family in the yard, perched on his pillows during a toast in his honor, a young man of 36 dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children and having tried everything to survive.
&quot;In the last six months, three to five beds are always occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45,&quot; Dr. Christian Martel says with concern.
53% of the patients admitted to the Victor-Gadbois shelter come from home and 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is believed that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients who have entered the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor-Gadbois Orphanage and the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is this large gap in Quebec&#39;s healthcare system that makes many palliative care physicians wary of legislation legalizing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by palliative care luminaries Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, declaring their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec&#39;s healthcare system is not strong enough to ensure the right to high quality palliative care before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room, in terrible pain, and no one took the necessary measures to alleviate them.
I fear that patients wish to die only because they do not receive adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists are trying to save patients until the last day, despite pessimistic forecasts.
Ellen Richard&#39;s hopes for survival were already minimal when she stopped debilitating chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she was sorry that I was stopping the fight, she says.
At the same time, she herself told me that my days were numbered!
There is no omnipotent care
Dr. Martel estimates that 90% of patients who ask for death thank the medical staff for not complying with their request, after the palliative care team eases their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not completely omnipotent in the fight against pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Palliative Home Care Society of Greater Montreal, patients are not responsive to pain relief in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until the moment of his death, either occasionally or constantly.
We can no longer pretend that we are unaware of these sufferings.
Increasingly, patients who fail to relieve pain will be able to access palliative sedation.
Patients suffering from pain always say the same phrase: &quot;I want to die.&quot;
But it doesn&#39;t necessarily mean &quot;I want to be euthanized&quot;, it means &quot;I want to feel better&quot;.
