The exact opposite of the current money exchange based on central banks, numbered transactions between the receiving parties with fees to process them.
Also, as is often the case with these technologies, a political vision is evident: the belief that the current monetary system of banking monopolies is leading to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible to dollars, euros...) and a secure BitTorrent-like exchange protocol that allows peer-to-peer file sharing.
About 200,000 transactions have already been registered from 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins for donations or as a means of payment.
The price of bitcoin, having peaked at $30 (€23) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later before returning to around $10 today (rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the worldwide exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB), in its virtual currency report released in October, took interest in the system.
He describes bitcoin as &quot;the most successful virtual currency&quot;, &quot;rivaling the dollar or the euro&quot; and &quot;similar to conventional currencies&quot;.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies in that the &quot;credits&quot; used to advance in a video game are earned by playing or can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by some central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes in the network are simultaneously ledgers, auditors, currency issuers, buyers, and sellers.
How does this network function?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two email addresses, much like email.
Only for each new payment, the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information relating to this transaction is electronically signed using a dual key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in the public ledger distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this ledger.
It goes through the solution of a mathematical problem sent to computers, the solver of which, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
We are talking about the file hashing phase, that is, converting a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers &quot;take&quot; a new transaction and add a number to it before &quot;hashing&quot; the whole thing together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many leading zeros).
Once this number is found, it is easy for other nodes to verify that it is correct.
The transaction is thus inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of deception, the user very quickly (less than ten minutes) wished to pay twice with the same money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, since they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the award is regularly halved, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible to one hundred millionth, which leaves a reserve...
The complexity of the task also increases with increasing computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
Websites providing Bitcoin services were attacked and bitcoins were stolen from reserves.
&quot;The defect exploited is not related to the protocol itself,&quot; says Pierre Noiset, who recently launched Paymium, a real-money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB has also reported the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this disadvantage.
Big players like Wikipedia refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron, from the Weizmann Institute of Science in Israel, analyzed the ledger and found that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
&quot;Giant sales&quot; were announced in November.
&quot;Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged,&quot; cheers Jon Holmqvist, who works at Coinabul, which converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noiset, another author of the tutorial on this currency, is a firm believer in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
His system, Paytunia, is the real-money equivalent of a credit card or contactless mobile phone payment, but it uses bitcoin to validate transactions, making it cheaper.
The owner has better control over his personal data and can thus be anonymous.
The system is easy to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough just to provide an address that can be &quot;photographed and recognized&quot; by the phone, Pierre Noiset clarifies, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general tendency to revise hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal ones.
&quot;Before Bitcoin is established, it will take some time, but 2013 could be a turning point,&quot; he predicts.
The ECB in its report proposes, by the way, to reconsider the various risks that are considered to be elevated today, if this system is successful.
We left Afghanistan.
What&#39;s next?
French troops left their area of responsibility in Afghanistan (Kapisa and Surobi).
NATO and the Americans should follow them at the end of 2014.
The time has come for the Afghan army to regain control of its territory, and for the Afghans to choose their future, not relying only on us.
We suffered mainly Afghan peasants, whom we considered as terrorists.
And we ourselves, with 88 soldiers killed, and wounded and crippled.
The Taliban are made up of foreign extremists, former commanders hiding in Pakistan, but also often peasants who reject the presence of a foreign army, as they did under the USSR.
They want to protect their traditions, old and archaic, even if they are joined by jihadists, Pakistanis, Arabs, Uzbeks, Tajiks.
They are tolerated and sometimes helped by local rebels, but they will no longer exist as soon as the West becomes more delicate.
The departure of the French troops from the base of Nijrab, which I observed from the heights of the hills planted with almond trees thanks to French loans, proceeded in order.
Convoys of trucks and armored vehicles, escorted by helicopters, reached Kabul without being attacked.
From the end of 2014, there will be no Taliban invasion of Kabul.
Circumstances have changed since their irresistible advance from 1994 to 1996.
At that time, Kabul was empty, the country was on fire and blood due to the struggle between various factions.
Their taking control of the country was then perceived as a kind of liberation, a return to security.
Afghan women paid the price for the obscurantism of these peasants, in which they were surpassed by al-Qaeda, but their situation has not improved even today.
The former Mujahideen, the Afghan government and the current Taliban are united in their desire to keep women in a subordinate position.
The main characters of the anti-Soviet war returned to power in 2001.
They have become speculators, seizing state land to resell it as a building block to repatriates returning from Iran and Pakistan using huge US subcontracts.
They are discredited; most of them, by the way, did not even fight themselves.
The people, I heard in the countryside, want a government that is not thieves.
Many young people want to leave, as those who succeeded by American generosity will leave: the outflow of capital is significant.
Young people are tired of the war and its ideology.
They lived in the modern world during their exile in Iran or Pakistan, they appreciated its benefits.
About 65% of the population is under the age of 25; Kabul now has 5 million inhabitants, one-fifth of the total population.
The public schools in the cities are filled with both boys and girls.
It is necessary to provide jobs for these young people who will not want to return either to the obscurantism of the old parties or to the corruption of some leaders.
Everyone, including armed militants, loves mobile phones, television and Turkish soap operas that represent the modern world and are watched everywhere.
At the moment there is an army.
Will the authorities that will command it be considered legitimate?
The old commanders who waged the anti-Soviet struggle are already taking steps to restore the provincial squads, which would not be subordinate to the central government.
Afghanistan, a mountainous country with strong local differences, should be decentralized to a certain extent, along the lines of Western countries, but the United States wanted to turn it into a centralized state with a strong presidential power, eliminating the post of prime minister that had existed since the 1964 Constitution.
President Karzai does not want foreign control, especially ahead of the April 2014 elections.
But his country has depended on foreign aid since the 1950s and even earlier.
Industry has not been put on its feet, not a single dam is functioning, not a single irrigation system has been repaired.
Everything is imported; nothing is produced except vegetables and fruits.
Priority is given to private initiative.
In a country ravaged by thirty years of war, government control of the infrastructure would be necessary.
There were rumors that Afghanistan had enormous mineral wealth.
This only reinforced the feeling that Western countries were there only to take over.
Without the energy to process iron ore or copper locally, without the means of transport to export it over the mountains, there is no mining.
The Chinese have almost abandoned the Mes Ainak copper mine, leaving international archaeologists (funded by the World Bank) to excavate the huge Buddhist complex and remain the province&#39;s biggest employers.
It is also necessary that one day Afghanistan and Pakistan, on which imports and exports depend to a large extent, restore normal relations.
The withdrawal of French combat units was completed on 20 November.
The new cooperation agreement provides for the preservation of traditional assistance: a lyceum for girls, for boys, the French language department at the university, the French Institute, cooperation in the military, legal, medical and agricultural fields, support for the archaeological delegation.
Since 2009, in an effort to &quot;win hearts and minds&quot; and fulfill the impossible task of combining aid with offensive operations, the Ministry of Defense&#39;s &quot;civil-military activities&quot; service (Cimic), abolished in 2012, along with a small French NGO, has contributed to numerous public works and activities aimed at restoring agriculture in dozens of mountain villages.
These works, with the intensive involvement of local labor, were able to help contain the rebellion: irrigation, wells, drinking water, reforestation, fruit trees, soil protection and an increase in arable land.
What will we leave as a memory of ourselves by spending two billion euros on military spending?
A much more modest budget would help improve the living conditions of the local population, which are very harsh in these valleys, located often at an altitude of more than 2,000 meters above sea level.
The Embassy has received dozens of written requests for small agricultural work from local communities in the province of Kapisa.
To get rid of the rebellions led by foreign factions, which is what the farmers want, they told me, they need to give them a little non-military support that is well controlled and goes directly to them.
Difficult birth of the Egyptian Constitution
This is a new risky move by President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is divided more than ever, on the issue of a constitutional declaration that temporarily gives it emergency powers, he decided to play all in.
Taking everyone by surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Exactly one week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to complete the work.
It will soon be two years since Egypt is relying on a draft text that has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal conflicts.
This new initiative only deepened the division of the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his &quot;autocratic delirium&quot;, continuing to &quot;break his word&quot; and &quot;trample the right.&quot;
In the camp of his followers, they are sure that this is a way to end the institutional and political crisis by speeding up the transition process.
The referendum must be held within fifteen days.
A very short period of time which causes the Brethren to abandon their intention to explain the text to the Egyptians, article by article.
It is also a way for the president to restore public and democratic legitimacy as discontent rages across the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote yes, he stated in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Moreover, the call for an accelerated vote is like an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: &quot;Either you vote for my text, or I keep emergency powers for myself,&quot; which is supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, the 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted in favor of the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not respond to the challenge.
In mid-November, shortly before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, feeling unable to get their point across.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society have done the same.
In order to reach the required quorum, 11 reserve members were hurriedly added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, in most cases, the articles were voted unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, were amused by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day arose around ... the time for prayer, since some members of the committee felt that the hours of the Constituent Assembly were not set correctly.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday, consists of 234 articles.
The object of public attention, Article 2 ultimately remained identical to the article in the 1971 Constitution, stating that &quot;the principles of Sharia are the fundamental source of law.&quot;
Salafist parties, for which the implementation of Islamic law is one of the main requirements, hoped to replace &quot;principles&quot; with &quot;rules&quot;, which would enable their more rigorous application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
&quot;Hypocrisy,&quot; answer the liberals, who see this as just PR.
Because, in their opinion, the Islamization of the Constitution occurs through other articles.
They point in particular to Article 220, which grants Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular with regard to the verification of compliance with Sharia law.
According to Sophie Pommier, an expert on Egypt, this is worrisome because &quot;the people called upon to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.&quot;
We can see the rise of theocracy.&quot;
Many liberals are also aghast at the fact that the next chancellor of this university is likely to be far less moderate than the current one.
“At the moment there is no specific religious intervention.
With this constitution, we remain within civil law.
Most of the jurists who worked on this text are not ulema, but people with a university education, some trained in the French system,&quot; reassures Alexis Bloe, who is preparing a dissertation on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he admits that “there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, since the terms used in it are borrowed from religious vocabulary.
This applies in particular to &quot;fiqh&quot; [Islamic jurisprudence - ed.].
And in the future, the question may arise how competent civilian judges are to rule on this.&quot;
Apart from its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is being criticized as it gives broad powers to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood claims they are much reduced from what they were under the old regime.
Another controversial point: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the wishes of the military, the defense budget will be considered not in Parliament, but in the National Defense Council.
Also, the trial of civilians in military courts will not be prohibited, despite requests from human rights associations.
The latter also expressed concern about the text, which they consider detrimental to freedom.
Blasphemy remains liable, and insult is now prohibited, which can have serious consequences for freedom of speech, and especially freedom of the press.
In addition, none of the articles talk about women&#39;s protection anymore, emphasizes Heba Moraef of Human Rights Watch.
According to her, the only positive aspect is the prohibition of torture in Article 36.
A word that did not appear in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
Supporters of the head of state, in turn, will take to the streets on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists are waiting for holy places, the Navel of the Earth and a sea of brine
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and pristine nature.
&quot;AiF&quot; identified the five most important reasons why you need to visit Israel.
Let&#39;s bow to holy places
It is worth visiting the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is believed that God&#39;s grace descends on everyone who enters this &quot;font&quot;.
And Galilee is the place of Jesus&#39; miracles: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
Here Jesus appeared before the disciples after the resurrection.
But most of the shrines are in Jerusalem.
Believers here pass the Path of Sorrow or the Way of the Cross of Jesus (in Latin - Via Dolorosa).
It starts at the fortress of Anthony - Praetorium - where there was a trial, and through the streets of the Old City leads to the Church of the Holy Sepulcher on Mount Golgotha - to the place of the Crucifixion, the Anointing Stone and the burial place of Jesus.
There is also a symbolic Christian Navel of the Earth, symbolizing the salvation of mankind.
And the monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was erected on the site where, according to Christian legend, a tree grew from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem, there is also the holiest place for the Jews - the Wailing Wall, left over from the temple, destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes here, which then come true.
Take a vertical trip
The ruins of the fortress of Massada were left from a secret refuge from enemies, which Herod the Great built in 25 BC. for your family.
They are located on sheer cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
And only those who are fond of mountaineering can get to them on their own.
The rest is delivered to this historic peak by a cable car lift.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the famous Hermon ski resort, where in the winter months there is a huge influx of tourists.
A shuttle bus delivers to it from the foot of the mountain.
The total length of ski slopes is 45 km.
According to an old legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are about 300 museums in this country.
You can&#39;t visit them all in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting, are worth a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (parliament).
It contains the oldest Qumran manuscripts, or the Dead Sea Scrolls, found in the caves of the Judean Desert, and about 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Tel Aviv Museum of Art is also worth a visit.
In its exposition, the canvases of the impressionists and expressionists of Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cezanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso are widely represented.
In Akko, you can visit the Al Basha Bath Museum, which consists of several halls of ancient Turkish baths with models of visitors and attendants of that time.
In Caesarea, it is worth visiting the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire the sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are no guides and souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are strictly not accepted.
The fifth - the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells about one of the most dramatic pages of history.
The most tragic section - the children&#39;s memorial - was built in memory of the 1.5 million children killed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You go into it - and you find yourself in absolute darkness.
Stars twinkle.
And the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
improve your health
The three main resort areas of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead Seas.
Each of them has swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
It is interesting that people swim in the Red Sea even in the winter months, since the water temperature there does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius, and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and people swim there all year round.
By the way, this most extraordinary sea in the world is located at the lowest point on the planet - 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a brine that easily keeps afloat even those who cannot swim at all.
The landscapes around are unrealistically beautiful.
People come here to undergo a course of treatment with the use of salt water - brine, and healing mud, and to treat their health with dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes mellitus, in order to put in order shaky nerves.
Touch the secrets of antiquity
They are kept by the old part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
The famous Sea Route passed through it, connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his ark, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists are very fond of wandering through the narrow streets named after the signs of the Zodiac.
They say that if you touch the walls on the street of &quot;your&quot; sign, Fortune will become favorable.
In Jaffa, you can meet newlyweds coming from all over Israel and even other countries for photo shoots.
And in Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can wander around the Roman theater, &quot;take&quot; the fortress of the Crusaders.
During the Roman period, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to the tourist
Going to Israel, don&#39;t worry about your imperfect English: in the country, about 30% of the population knows Russian.
It is better to take money on a trip not in euros, but in dollars, which are easy to exchange for shekels (now $ 1 - 3.8 shekels).
City transport is mostly buses, but Jerusalem has a high-speed tram, and Haifa has the only metro line in the country, consisting of six stations and connecting the Lower City with the Upper City.
In fact, this is an underground funicular.
Travel in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can travel with transfers for 1.5 hours.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, Shabbat is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets, shops, and public transport stop working.
Sunday morning starts the work week.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels - only kosher food, excluding pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes that combine milk with meat.
They offer a large selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts cooked with coconut milk, traditional Jewish hummus paste, a variety of sauces, balls of ground chickpeas - falalel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
But there are a lot of well-fed cats that imposingly &quot;walk by themselves.&quot;
In the evening, they can be seen sleeping even on the roofs of parked cars.
Purrs love crowded places and do not refuse treats.
Renting a car, depending on the brand, will cost from $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
Plus insurance - $15 per day.
A bike rental will cost 15 shekels. in a day.
Tickets to museums cost an average of 30 shekels.
The language of numbers
In 2012, over three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most of all, citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine came to travel and relax.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists visited the Promised Land, which is 51% more than in 2010, before the abolition of visas on February 9, 2011.
&quot;Great and mighty&quot; will bring to Moscow: migrants save money for the language
While deputies and human rights activists are arguing about what the law on mandatory language testing will give, scammers have already appeared in the country selling &quot;fake&quot; certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
For the most part, these are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their sole purpose is to earn money to support the families left behind.
On December 1, a law came into force, according to which every labor migrant will be required to take an exam for knowledge of the Russian language.
So far, this rule is valid only for those who intend to work in the service sector, housing and communal services, household and retail trade.
However, over time, the FMS promises, tests will become mandatory for all visitors.
Moreover, you will have to take not only the language, but also Russian history, and the foundations of legislation.
Language proficiency will have to be confirmed both for obtaining and for extending a work permit.
The exception is valid only for citizens of those countries where Russian is the state language.
People who managed to get certificates and diplomas of education before the collapse of the USSR in 1991 are not subject to the law.
Benefit, doom and protection of rights
The network of examination points will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Russian Language Institute, Peoples&#39; Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants will be able to take tests in all cities; more than 160 such centers have already opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce testing was supported by both State Duma deputies and the Federal Migration Service.
But human rights activists, before the law came into force, many times managed to ask the press the question: what will it actually give?
What will change the mandatory knowledge of the language for both Russians and visitors themselves?
First of all, representatives of the migration service answer, this will reduce the number of people suffering from &quot;labor slavery.&quot;
Many people are now talking about protecting the rights of labor migrants, explains Viktor Sebelev, head of the Russian Federal Migration Service in Tajikistan.
The protection of their rights must begin before they leave.
Only a system of organized recruitment will allow 90% to solve the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise for migrants without a profession, education, who do not know the language, who do not have a medical examination.
Without understanding the language, - Sebelev is sure, - the future migrant is doomed to face unscrupulous people who, under the guise of help, will put him a &quot;voucher&quot; in a terrible cramped barracks, where he and dozens of his kind will languish for months without food and documents, working 12-14 hours per day.
We receive a lot of complaints from our migrants.
&quot;At home, they are promised one thing, but upon arrival they are deceived, their passports are taken away, and the promised salary is not paid,&quot; Tolib Sharipov, head of the Main Department of Labor Migration of the Tajik Ministry of Justice, confirms.
Do not swear, nasyalnik!
Nevertheless, so far many citizens of the Central Asian republics who are going to work in Russia admit that they not only do not know the language of the country they are striving for, but also have difficulty writing in their own.
Of course, this is not so much their fault as a misfortune: few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get even a sensible primary education.
After all, their families have nothing to even feed their children, not to mention the fact that they are decently dressed, shoes and equipped for school.
Growing up to adolescence, these guys go to work as soon as possible.
It is difficult if it is bad with knowledge of the language, they admit.
&quot;You feel humiliated and inferior.&quot;
True, human rights activists note one important point with regard to the law on language.
Testing will be carried out only for those migrants who have a legal status.
If there is no status, there will be no exam, no subsequent official work.
Meanwhile, most of the guest workers are still living in Russia illegally.
&quot;Welcome or No Trespassing&quot;
Many of the visitors claim that it is not so easy to get official status in our country.
The reason is bureaucratic obstacles and all the same language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But a fake registration can be done quickly and for only one and a half thousand.
Russian police officers know that we mostly have false documents, no registration, hence the cases of extortion.
&quot;They ask for a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea,&quot; Tajik citizen Umed Khushkadamov shared with reporters.
&quot;Fly, don&#39;t be stingy, buy a painting&quot;
On the very first day of the entry into force of the language law, it turned out that not only migrant registration documents are false.
Several &quot;fake&quot; certificates of passing language tests have already been confiscated by the FMS.
Fake papers are printed on a conventional color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get them for nothing: each of the migrants, who hoped in this way to make it easier for themselves to pass the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as expensive as the official testing procedure: it will cost a labor migrant three thousand.
Both authorities and human rights activists agree that the main task for the near future is to protect the system from corruption, so that &quot;crusts&quot; cannot simply be bought.
In the meantime, the authorities can promise guest workers who failed to successfully pass the test the first time, time to study the basic language course.
In addition, visitors who do not know Russian will be offered work in areas that do not involve active communication with people.
Ministry of Internal Affairs does not take into circulation the illegal arms market
The share of crimes involving the use of legal weapons is extremely small
The Ministry of Internal Affairs of Russia proposes to tighten the law against owners of civilian weapons.
This is the government&#39;s response to recent incidents: Shots fired at weddings when there were no casualties, and the massacre by Moscow lawyer Dmitry Vinogradov that killed seven people.
The police want to ban the wearing of traumatic weapons in public places and raise the age at which you can get a gun license from 18 to 21.
The idea was supported by the head of the Duma Committee on Security and Anti-Corruption, Irina Yarovaya, and promised that amendments to the law on weapons would be submitted to the State Duma in the near future.
Not everyone is happy that the Russian authorities are trying to deal with the problem by &quot;tightening the screws.&quot;
An open letter appeared on the net, the authors of which - representatives of various public shooting organizations - demand that the &quot;senseless tightening&quot; be abandoned.
The percentage of hooliganism with a registered weapon is minimal, said forensic lawyer Vasily Lesnikov to the BBC Russian Service.
According to the statistics of the Ministry of Internal Affairs, during the six months of 2012, 142 crimes were committed with the use of firearms registered with the internal affairs bodies, while in total 1,168,000 crimes were recorded over the same period.
The authors of the open letter are confident that the tightening of legislation in the field of civilian weapons does not prevent the criminal from going to the &quot;black&quot; market.
Now, according to them, in Moscow you can find any weapon at a low price.
Meanwhile, the Ministry of Internal Affairs claims that they control the situation with the spread of illegal weapons.
Suppliers: from factories to officers
The &quot;black&quot; arms market is replenished through several channels.
There are five main such channels, says retired colonel Viktor Baranets, who worked for ten years in the structure of the Ministry of Education and the General Staff.
Screenshot of a site that accepts orders for weapons
The first is the &quot;army or military trace&quot;, that is, weapons that were stolen during the fighting in the Caucasus.
&quot;Weapons were dragged by both Russian officers and Caucasians themselves,&quot; says Baranets.
The next type of &quot;black weapon&quot; is the one stolen by criminals from law enforcement agencies.
Baranets explains that this includes both those carried away from police warehouses and those stolen directly from law enforcement officers.
Illegal &quot;trunks&quot; go on sale from military warehouses.
Explosions occurred frequently in many military depots.
&quot;There are proven versions that some of the arsons were done on purpose - to cover up the shortage,&quot; says the former military man.
Arms manufacturers are making their contribution, according to Baranets.
&quot;Now private arms factories are multiplying, which cannot withstand competition on the international market and throw weapons from under the floor to the black market, including Moscow,&quot; the expert says.
Another source of the &quot;black&quot; market is smuggling.
Especially a lot of pistols and machine guns come from poor countries, for example, Kyrgyzstan.
“They have their own production, sometimes handicraft, and a mafia has formed that organized the flow,” the former military man explains.
Where is the weapon from?
The experts calculated the approximate share of each of the sources of supply of illegal weapons to the &quot;black&quot; market.
