&quot;While deceiving the brain is average&quot;
The topic of augmented reality, popular among fans of modern technologies, has recently been taken mainly through the prism of special glasses.
First, in the summer at its annual conference, Google showed the working model, and then in November it became known that Microsoft had filed an application for the corresponding patent.
However, from a conversation with the head of the group of interactive 3D technologies at Microsoft&#39;s Cambridge laboratory, Sharam Izadi, it follows that for the scientists of this company, glasses are a passed stage.
They are attracted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, creating virtual open spaces.
- Please tell us in general terms what your research group is doing?
- We are engaged in the interaction of man with machines, but at the same time we are trying to push the boundaries of this interaction.
While humanity en masse is stuck at the stage of working with pixels on a flat screen, sometimes poking at them with a finger.
We want to look 5-10 years ahead and predict cardinal changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors are a step forward, and almost no Xbox today is sold without Kinect, because everyone is interested in gesture control.
- What else awaits us ahead?
- Despite the fact that Kinect brought interaction to the physical level, a lot still happens on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input of information has improved (the system receives more data), but the output is not very good yet.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional display systems based on various technologies, including projective ones.
We need to release the computer world into our physical world, to make it more tangible.
To do this, however, it is necessary to recognize not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we will be able to supplement the real world with virtual objects in a much more convenient form.
And first of all - to hell with these stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
A popular item, but isn&#39;t it overrated?
- It definitely cannot be called a panacea - the question of privacy arises, because you do not always want to notify others about your actions and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but each in its own niche.
For example, to control devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not over sweeping ones, but over such mean, short ones.
At the same time, gestures were filmed not by the camera of the device, but by a wrist bracelet, which recorded the movements of bones and muscles.
While it is large, but theoretically it can be reduced to the size of a wristwatch.
But in general, the future belongs to a mixed type of control, for example, gesture + voice.
- How is that?
- For example, how do you ask me to give you this can of soda?
You say and show at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, it will be very difficult to recognize.
- So you want to force users to adapt to what the machine can or cannot currently do?
- Not necessarily, but this is a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will mainly have to work on the development of new types of sensors that will allow us to more accurately determine human reactions.
These can be, for example, laser sensors, they provide good depth resolution, which is very important.
- If we talk about your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your complaints about modern cameras?
Not enough resolution, depth or something else?
- In principle, the current generation is what we can build on in our work on three-dimensional recognition.
Of course, it would be nice to get 8 megapixels at 1000 fps.
But it&#39;s not the megapixels themselves, but the quality of the matrix and depth.
From the last point of view, all current technologies are not good enough for us - this adds work to algorithm designers.
That is, we must remember not only about the resolution along the X and Y axes, but also Z.
Also very important is the speed, the number of frames per second.
Human movements are quite dynamic, and the current 30 fps is frankly not enough, especially for gestures.
Steven Betysches from our Redmond lab made a touch sensor with adjustable processing delay - from 1 to 100 ms, and modern serial sensors are closer to the second (60-100) indicator.
Not everyone understands how much this affects the interaction of man and machines.
In my work, the equivalent of such a device would be very useful to me, only it does not require touches, so that there are more frames per second.
- Do you need to increase the number of cameras?
- Kinect now has three &quot;cameras&quot;, one of which is actually an infrared emitter and the other is an echo receiver.
And now the third camera is, in fact, a conventional sensor in the visible range.
It is not used to determine the depth of an object.
Potentially more cameras could solve the problem...
Or aggravate it by increasing the required amount of calculations.
It would be nice to create a flexible version of the Kinect, play with the curvature of the cameras and see how it helps in 3D positioning.
- As far as I remember, Microsoft, unlike Google, did not present its glasses to the public.
Don&#39;t you think that in terms of everyday use of augmented reality technologies, glasses are one of the most promising platforms?
- Of course, it’s not very convenient to walk around holding a smartphone in raised hands all the time, but here’s what I think: the coolest option would be a “transitional” augmented reality, when based on a cloud platform you could switch from glasses to a smartphone, a projection display and so on everywhere.
Glasses are a very personal device, this is their strength (only you see private things), and at the same time their weakness - glasses-based augmented reality will not allow you to work on virtual objects together with other people.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark from Iron Man, but also to a mere mortal.
There is one problem that critics of this idea often point out: no tactile feedback!
Hands feel nothing!
What responses is your group preparing for this challenge?
- In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh breakthrough in the interaction between man and machine.
I think the eighth may well be the addition of tactile sensations.
In the meantime, one of the interesting tricks is the use of the second hand as a kind of substrate for the image.
It registers clicks perfectly!
But there are also technologies that are really aimed at making these &quot;pictures in the air&quot; tangible - for example, the interference of several directed ultrasonic beams at a certain point where the finger is located gives a feeling, but so far it is very weak - as if you were blown on the pads.
There are also bracelets on the wrists that affect the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
- Have you tried to trick the brain?
Make him think that he feels what he supposed to feel at the moment when he sees something?
- That&#39;s a good idea, we haven&#39;t tried it yet.
Here lies another task that will have to be fought for a long time - how to make a person who is physically in a very limited space believe that he is walking on an open, almost endless one - we are also working on the concepts of treadmills (not at all the same as in clubs) , moving platforms, and huge balls.
While deceiving the brain turns out to be average, the work is still very much for many years.
That&#39;s what makes working on virtual reality so attractive to the researcher - many things are in their infancy.
