At a meeting of the Audit Committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint project between the Czech and German sides, in which the public procurement legislation of both countries was compared.
What exactly was it about?
This refers to a parallel test, which we probably started two years ago.
Simply put, the point is that European legislation states how public procurement should take place, followed by national legislation and then also application in practice.
All the information was collected and, even with the still unfinished check, interesting differences were found - in other words, our legislation can be &quot;accurate and error-free&quot;, but in practice we are inferior to Germany in some respects.
It follows that it is not enough to create more and more precise rules, it is necessary to focus on the application of the law itself.
And actually how this project can help you, what does it mean for you?
It is this kind of joint control that can contribute to efforts to stop the clarification of laws, the reduction and improvement of restrictions, because this does not lead to a positive result.
Economics means getting the right thing for a reasonable (but not always low) price to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal behavior.
But it is not certain that we will achieve this by lowering the order limit.
It is possible that this system will be filled with &quot;papers&quot; so that those who wish to find loopholes in this system will find them much easier than if the limit had not been lowered.
You are talking about internal problems in the practical application of public procurement legislation.
And how does the control system in Germany work?
Is there such an organization as our KRU (Control and Auditing Department) or does it work differently?
As far as the institutions are concerned, the Bundesrechnungshof acts as our KRU, arranged according to our principle, there is also a collegium that works a little differently, but basically both institutions function in the same way.
In addition, the powers are similar to a certain extent, but since Germany has a federal structure, there are audit units at the level of the federal states - in this their system is somewhat different from ours.
BRH can only manage federal money, we have state funds.
Public funds in our regions and municipalities are controlled at the level of federal accounting chambers.
As for local legislation, is it easier there than here?
In general, I would not like to compare without specific data, but in some respects Germany can be taken as a model, but it cannot be definitely said that it is better in everything.
Is it because they are better at controlling?
Definitely not, but again, I don&#39;t like these comparisons.
But it must be said that even exemplary countries face many problems.
Otherwise, they wouldn&#39;t get any benefit from working with our office, right?
If we talk about domestic legislation, how did the amendments to the Public Procurement Law affect your institution, are the consequences somehow manifested?
Considering that the legal force of these amendments is rather short, it has not yet manifested itself in any way in our control works.
Since we are post-checking, some delay must be taken into account.
We take this into account only in the process of preparing future reviews - we have started using our new tool &quot;risk detection&quot; through which we have run nearly 14,000 government contracts. We have analyzed them. There, of course, these changes will manifest themselves, because restrictions change, the conditions of some types of tenders change, and so on.
Do you think the approval of this law will bring benefits or additional burden on the bureaucracy system?
I think that this law is definitely a step in the right direction, and I hope it will be confirmed.
The problem that may arise is that the rules will &quot;tighten&quot; and it will not be possible to comply with them.
Under the functioning of the previous rules, controlled enterprises are linked to the supplier (for example, regional operational programs - to the regional council) in that any non-compliance with the law on public procurement means a violation of budgetary discipline.
Is it worth it in this case to tighten the law in this way?
I think not in this way.
The system should exclude those who want to capture and abuse, but not punish those who make a technical error that does not affect the decision.
Such a system will only create more pressure on the bureaucracy.
And then how to get out of this situation?
Let&#39;s realize that this path will lead nowhere.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the SDS will not bother entrepreneurs with checks on the so-called Schwartz system. What does it mean?
&quot;Schwartz-system&quot; prohibited or permitted?
The law must be established in some way, and if it prohibits something, then the prime minister cannot resist the work of the bodies that are charged with the duty to check and enforce obligations.
You can say, &quot;We&#39;ll change this law and fix it,&quot; but you can&#39;t say that we&#39;re going to pretend like nothing&#39;s happening.
The Public Procurement Law contains rather strict rules on how and what should be formally carried out, and rightly so. This will protect government purchases.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic when the candidate with the best offer is disqualified only because of formal shortcomings.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly, which, in my opinion, we lack.
