Shimon Ornest: At concerts we want to accumulate positive energy
What do you think about the end of the world coming in less than a month?
This is just one of the many disturbing pieces of news we humans fall for so easily.
Together with the band The Tap Tap, we constantly joke about this and say that we are the only band in the world that can gather enough positive energy to delay or prevent the end of the world.
Moreover, in December you are going to play absolutely unique three concerts against the end of the world.
Could you tell readers more about this?
This is a nationwide fundraising event that we have been planning for the past two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, which is announced to end on December 21 at 11:10.
The day before this event, on December 20 at 21:00, three concerts in Prague, Brno and Ostrava start in parallel.
They will end, roughly speaking, at the moment when the May calendar ends on the island of Kiribati in the Pacific Ocean, whose time zone is 12 hours earlier than ours.
Who came up with this idea?
Initially it was my idea, then we came up with everything together with our artist Gonza Augusta.
In addition to the fact that we want to accumulate enough positive energy and prevent the end of the world, we also want to think together with the public about the state of this world we will one day pass on to our children.
On the occasion of the end of the May calendar, we have created a unique collection of items from shoes, T-shirts, bags and original keys against the end of the world. These things can be bought on the website www.e-tap.cz and thus support us at the same time.
The Tap Tap, along with other musicians, also performed an anthem against the end of the world, called &quot;The End of the World Canceled&quot;.
Will the anthem already loved by YouTube listeners be played at these benefit concerts?
Of course, at the very end, if in the end everything works out and the end of the world does not come.
It will be sung by all performers at all concerts at the same time.
The hymns will also be played simultaneously live on Czech television.
The words to this song were written and played the role of Jesus in the video by Tomas Ganak, also Xindl X...
How did you start working with them?
We also cooperate with other persons of the Czech cultural life as we organize many charity events and concerts.
We try to actively involve them in these projects.
It turned out that many people like to work with us, they are interested.
What will the proceeds from the concert against the end of the world go to?
For the purchase of equipment for the barrier-free educational center STUDEO, for the sixth year now we have been working in this way with the civil association Tap at the Jedlicky Institute.
Teachers regularly visit the students of the Jedlicky Institute schools and hold fun and interesting events with them.
The students themselves do not have the means to go to the teachers, and we try to provide them with this opportunity in this way.
As part of the project for the additional construction of the Jedlicky Institute, a separate building will appear in the future, to which we will move with this project.
Each concert will feature several musical groups and performers.
What were the selection criteria?
We tried to create a program that would interest all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Barta, The Tap Tap, Marian Bango and Jiri Suchy will perform in Prague.
All details can be found on the website www.kpks.cz.
Are you planning any similar &quot;grand events&quot; in the future?
In May we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring festival and here, of course, we will prepare an interesting program with interesting guests.
Next year we would love to perform at the Czech National House in New York, and personally, if we are in the USA, I would very much like to perform in Washington and Chicago.
As for abroad, you have serious plans, you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you manage the road in terms of organization and logistics??
It&#39;s not as scary as it seems at first glance.
We have five participants in electric wheelchairs, their wheelchairs must travel in the luggage compartment, plus a large amount of cargo and tool boxes.
However, so far they&#39;ve handled it with no problems. Czech Airlines ČSA and British Airways have always been excellently prepared for us, which surprised me so many times.
Even in Moscow, where we recently returned from, everything went without problems.
Thanks to travel abroad, you can compare different countries in terms of accessibility, public attitudes towards people with disabilities, and so on.
What have you experienced so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other countries where everything functions better than ours, in Russia we have seen that in the east it is still at a basic level.
Compared to Prague, there are a lot of barriers in Moscow, and it is still a novelty for a person to move independently in an electric wheelchair in the city center.
Also, such banal things as giving way to a disabled person in an elevator are not in use there.
Fortunately, there are already emerging public organizations that are trying to draw people&#39;s attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what, on the contrary, do we constantly have to catch up with the advanced countries?
There are a lot of things, the level of performance of which is far behind.
But it is important to clarify that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the efforts of those people who are concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is quite normal that people with a severe form of disability move independently on the streets, can go to the toilet, to the museum, and anywhere ...
It is not very common there that a large number of people with disabilities take an active part in public life, in this we with The Tap Tap are a little ahead of them!
Respect for the public or accessibility is one thing, but the moment when famous athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers appear among us, then everything really starts to change.
While these are isolated cases - people with a strong will.
The Tap Tap is a very popular group at the moment, but going back two years, what made you start it in 1998?
I entered the Jedlicky Institute as an educator, there were many young people around me who wanted to do something.
And since I myself am a musician and also play the saxophone, together with a colleague I organized an interesting music circle.
Well, over time, as our presenter Ladya Angelovich says, it got a little out of control (laughs).
Popularity has come only in recent years, or am I confusing something?
It&#39;s true, it helped us that we started to join the famous singers and actively work on the promotion of the group.
We came to the conclusion that the work that no one can evaluate, in fact, as if it does not exist.
Thanks to the funds of the European Union, we can afford qualified teachers, equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to promote The Tap Tap so well?
From the very beginning, I felt their potential in being able to do something extraordinary.
Show business is full of things that imitate one another.
This is logical, everything new is accepted with caution, and it lasts a long time.
There are very few rare items, but I dare say Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us, of course, is pity, this is natural ...
But this pity is completely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not some suffering and all neglected individuals that we should feel sorry for.
They are people who can live a full life and develop, of course, only on the condition that they have the necessary resources.
I say that if people with disabilities succeed, this is a shift not only for them, but for the whole society.
Has it been successful that you are the strict leader that many people think you are?
If we want to do quality work, we must be uncompromising in many things and maintain a certain discipline.
But I think it&#39;s okay.
Some people come to us with a romantic performance and fly in the clouds, and when they find out that they have to go to rehearsals twice a week, attend preparatory courses and spend a lot of time on the road, they lose enthusiasm very quickly.
But this happens in any group that wants to work and achieve something.
There are currently twenty members of The Tap Tap.
How many were there at the beginning in 1998?
Only one Ladya Angelovich.
We are an open group, people come and go, you can&#39;t prevent it.
For those who have the desire and willpower, our doors are always open.
