Poland and space.
Last week, at the European Space Agency ministerial meeting, Poland was admitted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency, as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of the ESA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the following years took an active part in a number of ESA projects.
But Poland began its path to space much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in flights into space, but this was not always met with understanding.
Let me remind you, for example, of the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933, presented ideas from his pioneering work &quot;Introduction to Cosmonautics&quot; at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory.
The ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Peltri and André Louis Hirsch Prize for &quot;Introduction to Astronautics&quot;.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned above, later became a great promoter of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a well-known world promoter of astronautics, and his contribution was appreciated, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway trolley equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remained unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It is not even clear whether a rocket should have been used to accelerate or decelerate the trolley.
Information about this trolley is known only from the press of that era.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The study was carried out by the Armament Technology Section in cooperation with professors Mieczysław Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzycki.
From the surviving materials it can be seen that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photoelectric fighter rocket, which was proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in the specialized press, and the following year, the work &quot;Air torpedo rocket and aircraft bomb rocket&quot; by the author Leliva-Kzhivoblotsky was published.
Both projects were developed for the military use of rocket engines.
Before the war itself, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were handled by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, the work ended due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work devoted to astronautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The society was first mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal &quot;Problems&quot;, which published four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would deal with astronautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
From the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (POA) tried to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and already in the fall, the POA became its full member.
And the following year, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), the first chairman of the POA, became deputy chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PHA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which was the first Polish rocket to carry out a scientific study.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, capable of covering a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, a two-stage RM-2 rocket was tested on the Bledovsky wasteland.
This rocket was about 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could cover 14.5 km, and its task was to observe the high-altitude wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The Meteor-1 rocket, developed between 1962 and 1965, became the successor to the first RM-type missiles.
The rocket was conceived as a two-stage rocket, with an overall length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1V - 0.34 liters, and Meteor-1C - 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 rocket was being developed at the Aviation Institute, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket with a launch weight of 380 kg was capable of launching a payload weighing 10 kg to a height of about 60 km.
Then versions of Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland&#39;s accession to COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Interkosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978, the Polish pilot Miroslav Germashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
Repeal of the public works law is not the solution to the problem.
Last week, the constitutional court annulled the public works law.
The resolution caused a lively discussion in society.
Undoubtedly, it will be interesting to look at this issue from a broader point of view.
Liberal-oriented economic systems in the EU, as well as in the globalized world, are based on the principle of multiple, unregulated economic competition.
In essence, this means that individual economic units, national economic systems, are in constant conflict with each other.
This is due to the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital, together with unbridled financial speculation.
As a result of a significant difference in the cost of labor (wages), price tension arises.
This concept should be understood as a state when a manufacturer, by delivering a cheap product, tries to survive in economic competition by &quot;knocking down&quot; the cost of a competitor in order to take a large part of the market for himself and, thus, increase his own income.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either the transfer of production abroad, or cheap purchases abroad, or disappearance. As a result, unemployment rises in those countries where the cost of labor is, in comparison with others, high.
Since private capital does not bear any social responsibility, including for the unemployment it has produced, the inevitable costs of the state for social needs grow.
On the whole, the situation strengthens the unwillingness of gentlemen entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the public economic and social damage caused by them in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide specific statistics.
The unceremonious methods of private capital create situations at the level of the economies of individual states when the governments of countries are forced to compete with each other in order to artificially lower the social level of their population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments leave their own populations to the mercy of private capital, despite social decline.
This is reflected primarily in changes in the current legislation.
The goal is to economically force their people to submit to the dictates of private capital, primarily in the field of wages.
This acts as a system of economic coercion in the event of long-term unemployment and at the same time serves as a tool to curtail workers&#39; rights in the field of labor law.
As a result, the level of poverty increases, and with it the gap between the poor and the rich.
In Germany, for several years now, there has been a public distribution of food to the poor, who are not able to feed themselves with their own labor.
The number of these people is already approaching a million.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, cases constantly occur when employed people receive such a salary that the state must pay them extra so that they receive a living wage.
A similar scandal became known to the public in the case of additional employees of the Bundestag.
Economic measures in almost all the southern states of the EU are undoubtedly leading to the same state in which people under the pressure of a catastrophic decline in social status are forced to either emigrate, as was the case in the 19th century, or exist on a beggarly wage in the margins of society. in the hope that someday private investment capital will come to the country.
But the question is, where does it come from?
If capital comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, since the Chinese, Indian, Brazilian, Turk, Moroccan, Egyptian, African are still working for a share of European wages.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media assert ad nauseam that the state cannot participate in the capital of its own economy, that a controlled economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital stubbornly insists that the state should not interfere in the economy with managerial actions.
Next, the question should be answered whether private capital, which now practically controls politics and that very same state, does not act for its own selfish purposes?
The unequivocal answer is yes.
The proof is the existence of almost omnipotent and ubiquitous lobbies in all states.
As a result, we have a hopeless situation, manifested in corruption, provision of mutual benefits, in legislation, where almost everything deserves punishment, but is not a crime.
In Germany, the situation is such that the state ministries, due to lack of financial resources, entrust the development of draft laws to private law firms that are closely connected with industry.
Then these bills are approved by the Bundestag.
All power comes not from the people, as the Western-style constitution says, but from financially powerful groups that prefer their own interests.
Obviously, liberal-oriented democracy is now rapidly finding itself in a situation, as described by Appian in &quot;The Crisis of the Roman Empire in the Days of Caesar and Pompey&quot;:
Bribes, illegal receiving favors with the help of stones and swords.
Bribery and corruption flourished without any prohibitions, and people went to the polls with a pre-sold vote&quot;&quot;...decent people did not run for the position of ruler at all, in the end one day the state was left without a consul for eight months&quot;... .. &quot;They started in earnest to say that the only salvation in this terrible situation is autocracy and the need to choose an energetic person &quot;.. Appian thought it would be Pompey, but it was Caesar, who finally changed democracy to autocracy.
As in ancient times, modern society is dominated by its own reckless interests without regard to public interests.
Private capital is no longer inherently intended to be used for public purposes.
The present result is no different from the past: an unparalleled decline of the elite without any effort to bring about reforms of a deeper nature.
This means that we must look for the cause of the emergence of fascist and communist regimes in the reckless liberalization of the economic systems of the 19th and 20th centuries.
To date, the absence of these regimes and the existence of liberal-type democracy can be perceived as a certain pause, after which the next round is expected.
First of all, it is tragic that the current elite completely ignores the consequences of hundreds of thousands of victims in the future, the humanitarian and social catastrophes that we are already seeing, along with crimes against humanity, as we know it from old and new history.
Repeal of the public works law is not a solution, or at least not forever.
Under the pressure of competition both at the international and national and European levels, the government of the Czech Republic will be forced to continue to look for ways to further reduce the social level of the population.
Thus, this trend is systemic.
The solution is targeted political and social reforms that will strengthen the share of the state in the economy, strengthen the role of citizens in government and weaken the monopoly position of private capital in society in favor of the state.
