The film &quot;Operation&quot; Argo &quot;: When it&#39;s worse, call Hollywood
In November 1979, a mob of Islamist student demonstrators seized the US embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the deposed Shah Mohammed Reza Pahlavi, who fled after the revolution to the US, which had been his regime&#39;s patron for decades.
For the US administration, a positive outcome of the situation was not expected - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, because this could radically undermine the confidence of allies in other countries.
However, it was not able to achieve the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution led to the establishment of a theocratic regime.
This was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later reinforced by a failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were finally released 444 days later, after negotiations mediated by the Algerian government.
Their fate triggered a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The defeat in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter&#39;s defeat in the 1980 presidential election that ended with the election of Ronald Reagan.
The film, directed by actor Ben Affleck, &quot;Argo&quot; describes one of the episodes of the story that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six workers managed to escape.
After difficult ups and downs, they ended their journey at the residence of the Canadian Embassy.
The CIA, in cooperation with Canadian authorities, succeeded in getting them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover story according to which they left on Canadian passports as members of a film crew looking for a place in the country to film a sci-fi epic.
Combination of genres
The plan, devised by &quot;evacuation&quot; expert Tony Mendez, required the cooperation of Hollywood.
In order for the legend to be true, specialized magazines wrote about the film project, press conferences were held, a fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memoirs of Tony Mendez.
Affleck&#39;s film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called &quot;film opus&quot;, the story of a successful undertaking, a scam - an example can be a series of films about Ocean&#39;s friends.
The film constantly changes moods - on the one hand, documented scenes from Tehran (the credits show iconic historical photographs of events and the way in which the same situations were shown in the film - there are no big differences).
On the other hand, lightweight Hollywood passages interspersed with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then more scenes from the headquarters of the CIA and other institutions - men in suits discussing the situation at the negotiating tables, on the stairs of institutions, on the phone ...
Ben Affleck did a great job restarting his career.
From a ridiculed actor, he became a respected director, and his game ceased to be an object of ridicule.
Operation Argo is his third feature film, following the dark detective Goodbye Baby Goodbye (2007) and the thriller City (2010).
At the same time, this is the first Affleck film that is not filmed in the director&#39;s hometown of Boston.
The sense of place is one of the qualities that raised the director&#39;s earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows it in &quot;Argo&quot;, where Tehran &quot;plays&quot; Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place on the streets, reenacting real events - the opening scenes of the fall of the embassy are impressive in their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unforeseenness that arise when history suddenly changes somewhere.
Affleck and his colleagues achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake headquarters in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite well with these few, sometimes thinking something out - it all comes out not so elegantly there (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents an impending crisis at the Tehran airport and the runway chase looks rather far-fetched).
Argo&#39;s downside is that it&#39;s distracted by having to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman as their Hollywood counterparts are indeed very charming, but their characters would have deserved more space, and they are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck&#39;s film lacks a bit of drama, a film that can be watched with moderate interest, appreciating the production and the retro style that recreates the thrillers of the seventies.
But it&#39;s hard to grab.
However, this is enough to remind of one, still in a certain sense, living history, and also to testify to how exaggerated the notion of omnipotent and omniscient intelligence services.
Balloon Rules, Bananas and the Circus
The portal www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conducts an annual survey on the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to announce a competition for &quot;the most absurd regulation or project from the EU workshop&quot;.
&quot;We were spurred to this by the latest event, in which the EU plans to adopt a 40 percent quota for women in the administration of large European companies,&quot; Patrick Nager, the organizer of the survey, told Pravo.
Among the absurdities already put forward for the nomination is the European Court&#39;s recent decision to combine premium rates for men and women.
Until now, women have benefited from life insurance because for insurance companies they are objectively less at risk.
&quot;Further incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be submitted by people before the end of this year.
The voting itself will take place until the end of February 2013,&quot; Nager said.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the mandatory addition of biocomponents to fuel, which as a result is harmful to nature, as well as the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers only because they contain relatively small amounts of hazardous substances, or the cage size directive for chickens, owing to what this year eggs have essentially risen in price .
Also criticized was the de facto ban on the use of the term &quot;sandwich butter&quot; or the removal of classic light bulbs from sale.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters long.
The pan-European apparatus often makes a decision under the pressure of one or another trade or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually defended by some state or group of states (thus the Czech Republic now defends the demands of its banks even under the threat of a veto).
The interests of the lobby are as follows: for example, top-quality bananas in the European Union had to reach a length of 14 cm and did not dare to show &quot;anomalous curvature.&quot;
At the same time, the European Commission justified itself by saying that it was only harmonizing the existing disparate national rules that complicated trade.
The EU, despite the resistance of some states, nevertheless softened the standards regarding fruits and vegetables, citing the fact that existing directives would lead to wastage of products.
A candidate for winning the poll could also be last year&#39;s EU regulation, according to which balloons sold must be provided with a warning that children under eight years old cannot inflate them without adult supervision.
The EU has turned to US studies showing that balloons are a potential cause of death in children through suffocation when played.
A similar restriction now applies to children under the age of 14, who are prohibited from blowing the fair&#39;s horns.
Funny ideas are born at home too
Quite absurd is the rule concerning European officials themselves: anyone holding any official position in the EU cannot, given the sensitivity of the topic for Greece, use the name Macedonia, but must instead say &quot;FYROM&quot; (The former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia) .
The Bankovnípoplatky.com portal, in cooperation with the association of liberal economists &quot;Principle of non-intervention&quot; (Laissez Faire), proposed for voting, in addition to several of the above absurd rules, for example, the EU rule on the amount of food stocks in the territory of a member state.
The EU has set a maximum amount of food stocks that can be on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of its accession to the European Union.
Subsequently, the Czech Republic exceeded, for example, the established volumes of canned mushrooms, for which it was threatened with a large fine.
The organizers of the questionnaire were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having the sea, and the idea of providing subsidies for applying for subsidies.
But these ideas originated in Prague, not in Brussels.
&quot;We are at a disadvantage because we don&#39;t have the sea.
Let&#39;s ask the European Union for compensation,&quot; said in autumn 2004 the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSDP).
As an argument, he pointed out that the country had a high grain harvest, and as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, the state had full warehouses of stocks that had to be taken out.
For the fact that the Czech Republic is far from the ports, the EU, according to Palas, had to pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
As a result, the European Commission went to meet the Czech Republic, organizing a tender for the purchase of grain from countries that do not have access to the sea.
Subsidies for receiving subsidies were offered to villages by the Ministry for Regional Development, led by Minister Pavel Nemets (US-DEU), in particular, such subsidies were to be used to draw up an application for subsidies from Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are an exception
While rulings in member states are easily criticized, the EU&#39;s efforts to regulate and to make the EU function and develop more effectively are considered by many experts to be more recognizable.
A serious problem, according to experts, is the scooping of EU subsidies for projects that do not even have a hint of something in common with the deepening of European integration, but which the member states have achieved when discussing the budget.
It also stirs emotions among Czechs that, like other EU countries, the Czech Republic must fight in Brussels for the right to specific identification of its traditional products, and it does not always win in this competition.
Although the Czechs, after six years of fighting with the Germans and Austrians, retained the name &quot;Olomouc cheese curds&quot;, however, &quot;Tuzemsky rum&quot;, the traditions of which in our country go back to the 19th century, our producers had to rename to &quot;Tuzemak&quot;.
Only products made from cane distillate, and not from sugar beets, can be called rum.
In addition to the world-famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, marzipan from German Lübeck or Parma ham, the official list of registered EU products includes, for example, Karlovy Vary rusks, Pogorzelice and Trebon carp and Žatec hops.
Pardubice gingerbread and Hořice tubules can also be proud of the EU trademark.
