MVRDV architects prove that real adventures are not only in the imagination - with the example of Spijkenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
&quot;I find this building fun, it looks futuristic, finally we can see something interesting again,&quot; says Lisette Verheig, a passer-by on the side of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, says: &quot;No, this building is really beautiful.&quot;
But I ask myself: why do we need another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPads and e-books.
No one volunteers to go to such old-fashioned libraries these days, right?
Spijkenisse, an unremarkable bedroom town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this unfortunate circumstance, a decision was made several years ago to contribute to general education by building seven imaginary bridges, which are depicted on euro banknotes, in the form of beautifully painted miniatures made of reinforced concrete.
The success of this educational initiative was modest.
And then the city fathers realized that they had the only opportunity to overcome the statistics: to build a library here!
Winy Maas of Rotterdam architecture firm MVRDV, a master of bold bar charts and witty, sometimes even cynical builds, took on the challenge with his usual equanimity and showed up at the 2003 competitive audition with five books under his arm and a smirk on his face.
And while the members of the jury looked around in puzzlement and shrugged their shoulders, the impudent Maas folded a pyramid of size from his original gift and ended his speech in defense of his project with the following words: &quot;Dear citizens!&quot;
Here it is, my proposal: &quot;Book Mountain&quot; in Spijkenisse, the so-called Buckenberg!
Nine years later, this €30 million mountain has grown.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential buildings and townhouses with a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, Book Mountain won second prize in the 2012 Dutch Library of the Year competition.
The project also participates in the national Dutch competition of wooden structures in 2012.
Thus, a faceless suburb that previously had nothing to offer but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly city hall, whose white facades suggest a dairy, has become richer by one modern piece of architecture.
But most importantly, the first public cultural building in the history of this town appeared in Spijkenisse.
Long road to the book
First impression: a bookish Eldorado under a cheese hood.
There is only one lift, passing through the center of the mountain range, because true fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glazed on all sides, the space is bright and easy to see, fired brick floors and elegant street lamps unmistakably create the feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is recreated perfectly.
The gaze involuntarily searches for benches, dogs and boys and girls playing football.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
&quot;Usually there are bookshelves along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark room, usually uncomfortable and featureless,&quot; says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic space configuration on its head and pulled the reading area from the inside out.
The inner space of the book mountain is skillfully used: offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center and technical rooms are located in the center.
Particularly pleasing are the black bookshelves, which serve either as wall decoration, or as parapets, or as stair railings.
Their appearance, texture and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and civil engineers are at a loss as to what this unknown material is.
&quot;We wanted to work with recycled materials,&quot; explains Joop Trauborst, project manager representing the community of Spijkenisse, in accordance with the requirements of the standard.
And once, at an agricultural enterprise in Friesland, we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
For many years, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, millimeter-thick artificial fibrous material has been used as root lining.
It&#39;s cheap and saves time.
Thin textiles last one or two seasons, after which they can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas - for the first time in such volumes - was pressed into panels four centimeters thick.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the so-called landbauplastik (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous, durable material that smells a little like a new car and a little sneaker.
There are 105 steps leading to the top.
Those who overcome the path of almost 500 meters will be rewarded in the literary cafe not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and potted tree ficuses.
They take care of the atmosphere, and first of all about the correct air humidity on the literary mountain.
The cost of a new soul
&quot;It&#39;s hard to believe, but this building, despite the many glass surfaces, is an exemplary project in terms of ecology,&quot; says Trowborst.
For its heating and cooling, the heat of the earth is used.
Although the Book Mountain is under a glass cover, even on clear days the sun only gets inside for a short time.
Wide glulam trusses, perpendicular to the glass façade, provide shade and absorb most of the sun&#39;s rays.
The indoor climate is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic roller blinds.
Stefan Spermon, the IT skeptic mentioned above, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verheig was also already here.
As well as teacher of traditional Chinese medicine Cynthia Bogarde, who called Buckenberg &quot;the soul of Spijkenisse, which has long been missing.&quot;
Reason: A few weeks before the opening, each resident received an invitation to donate one book from their own collection.
These books were supposed to fill empty shelves on the shelves of the library, which was not yet fully stocked - at that time there were 70,000 books in it.
The idea worked.
Shelves are stacked to the top.
&quot;There is nothing worse than a half-empty library,&quot; says architect Winy Maas.
“I think that thanks to our invitation, now every resident is connected in some way to this new home.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it&#39;s just for decoration.
Thus, MVRDV succeeded in solving the royal task, which in professional jargon is called the creation of an identity.
Spijkenisse wrote his literary history.
And let them be very young and uneducated.
This is just the starting point for building an identity.
Szabo: Germans should play a bigger role
Germany abstained from voting on the recognition of Palestine.
In doing so, Berlin is teetering on a narrow diplomatic track, according to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-European relations.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first signaled that it would vote against the Palestinian bid for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained from voting.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that she also does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - while not being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
As a result, NATO passed this proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes it is.
