Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, and hepatitis.
Pediculosis pubis and scabies are both parasitic STIs.
What are the main affected groups?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of every five cases of syphilis reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydial infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungus), gonorrhea, and human papillomavirus.
The prevalence of HIV among heterosexual adults is relatively low in our country - however, about 20 percent of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydial infections are significantly more common than among other population groups.
According to European data, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
Among our youth, the human papillomavirus is also common.
How is the number of infections changing?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory registration.
The incidence of syphilis has more than doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011, according to the Robert Koch Institute.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011 there were about 2700 cases.
This is about one tenth less than the previous year.
What symptoms indicate a sexually transmitted disease?
Infectious diseases may cause ulcers in the genital area, complaints when urinating, discharge, pain in the lower abdomen, and blisters or lumps.
However, often they are not accompanied by pain and other symptoms and go unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but do not provide 100% protection.
Indeed, in part, the causative agents of sexually transmitted diseases can also be spread through contact infection and through close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examination, especially with frequent changes in sexual partners.
With early diagnosis, most STIs can be cured and long-term consequences can be avoided.
