Nevertheless, there is no poverty among Azerbaijani old people.
Mirzayeva receives 230 manats (approximately equal to the same amount of euros) as a monthly pension, which, for local conditions, is an amount on which one can live well.
And, perhaps, Mirzayeva&#39;s long-grown son is also right: &quot;Old people in our culture are deeply respected.&quot;
They live in a large family, are loved, cared for and happy.
Why not stay alive as long as possible
The word &quot;human right&quot; is missing from the constitution
The revolution has returned to Cairo.
Rival demonstrations in Cairo testify to the country&#39;s deep division.
The future constitution, based on Sharia, met with a fierce rebuff.
The Egyptian president did not skimp on pathos.
We have to create a transition.
&quot;And its success is my responsibility to the people and to God,&quot; he said on state television.
His speech was addressed to the entire nation, but primarily to Christian Copts, liberals, enlightened Muslims and non-religious Egyptians.
After all, all of them, still hopelessly divided in a confused opposition, are afraid.
Fear of a religious state on the Nile is at the mercy of the powerful Muslim Brotherhood.
Mohammed Morsi, almost apologetically, said that he had temporarily curtailed the competence of the constitutional court and expanded his competence &quot;in order to save the revolution.&quot;
However, what the 61-year-old engineer, who has a doctorate from the American University of Southern California, really wants to save is not entirely clear to the Egyptians and the whole world.
Will the judiciary be abolished?
In fact, 234 articles got through in the overnight 15-hour steeplechase at the Islamist-leaning 100-member constitutional convention, and this is partly worrisome.
As in previous constitutions, the draft states that the judiciary is based on the &quot;principles of Islamic law.&quot;
But what does &quot;principles&quot; mean?
This was and still is a matter of interpretation, and one fears that the Islamists will use the vague language and the resulting legal leeway to interpret sharia more strictly.
At least one new article hints at this: in all matters relating to Sharia, Al-Ashar University, the most important Islamist institution in the country, enjoying great authority in all Sunni Islam, should be involved in the advice.
This should not, but may mean, that the clergy oversee the legislation, which would de facto have the effect of limiting the judiciary.
Much of the draft constitution is subject to interpretation
One more problem: the jurisdiction of civilians to the military court should be preserved.
These courts during the period of Mubarak&#39;s rule served to suppress the opposition.
After the overthrow of the dictator, up to 11,000 civilians were in military custody.
Also, as stated in the project, the state must protect the &quot;true essence of the Egyptian family&quot; and &quot;support its morality and values.&quot;
Legally, this is formulated so vaguely that state institutions with the help of this article will be able to control even the content of cinema and literature.
In clear text, this means nothing more than censorship.
In general, no article directly establishes the equality of men and women.
But the other prohibits insulting and defamation of the Prophet Muhammad and his messengers.
But what an insult is and how it should be punished remains unclear.
The wording that &quot;insulting people&quot; is prohibited is also doubtful.
Will a caricature of the president or a joke about a lawyer be enough?
It&#39;s a matter of interpretation, as is much in this draft that Morsi is offering for signature, and which he says will &quot;very soon&quot; be submitted to the Egyptians for a referendum.
&quot;The Revolution is Back&quot;
