Tens of thousands of people gathered in unusual unanimity Friday evening in Cairo&#39;s Tahrir Square and vowed to destroy the document before it could go into effect.
&quot;The revolution is back and we will win,&quot; said Hamdeen Sabbahi, who finished third in the presidential election.
Mohammed ElBaradei, Nobel Peace Prize winner and former head of the international agency for atomic energy, said the draft constitution belongs &quot;in the dustbin of history.&quot;
Through Twitter&#39;s short news service, he accused Morsi loyalists of wanting to lead a &quot;putsch against democracy.&quot;
&quot;If he announces a referendum, we will go to his palace and throw him off,&quot; opposition leader Yasser Said said.
&quot;We are not tired yet, the blood of our brothers is not yet avenged,&quot; Egyptian media quoted opposition politician Khaled Ali as saying.
Many judges also said they did not want to observe the referendum, which would render it invalid.
&quot;The Quran is our constitution&quot;
The well-organized Muslim Brotherhood, in turn, called for an opposite demonstration, but as a precaution, not in Tahrir Square, but after mass prayer on the other side of the Nile in front of Cairo University.
It was attended by a large number of veiled women and Salafi adherents who shouted: &quot;The people demand the application of God&#39;s law.&quot;
They demanded from Morsi: &quot;Clean the country!&quot; and assured: &quot;The Quran is our constitution.&quot;
The struggle for power over the symbolic square where it all began provoked a state of almost civil war.
Morsi&#39;s followers were clearly reluctant to take that risk.
The Muslim Brotherhood said both opponents and supporters of the draft constitution spoke out loud and clear.
Now it&#39;s time to let the people decide at the ballot box in which direction the country should go.
The majority is for the Islamist project, it is considered a settled matter.
&quot;The concept of &quot;human rights&quot; is never mentioned&quot;
Hafiz Abu Saeda is furious at this forced constitutional process, which was supposed to last until February with the participation of all public forces.
The 48-year-old human rights lawyer and chairman of the Egyptian Organization for Human Rights (EOHR) has defended the Muslim Brotherhood when they were imprisoned or put on trial under Mubarak.
Not because he shared their worldview, but because human rights are indivisible for him.
For this he was beaten, sentenced, arrested.
And now the words &quot;human rights&quot; never appear in the new constitution, he regrets in an interview with &quot;Welt am Sonntag&quot;.
The expansion of Morsi&#39;s influence on all three branches of government in the state disappoints the lawyer.
These measures represent clear blows to the democratic rules of the game and will lead the Egyptians to a new dictatorship.
&quot;Instead of strengthening the civil state, the president de facto annulled it,&quot; Saeda laments.
After all, without civil society organizations, democracy cannot function.
Saeda feels that everyone has abandoned him, even the international community, which looks at the ideological struggle of directions on the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
There may be retribution for this.
A demonstrator in Tahrir Square warns: &quot;You are creating a monster that you cannot control.&quot;
Norwegian rakfisk: the most foul-smelling fish in the world?
Norway&#39;s population of five million has one of the highest standards of living not only in Europe but throughout the world.
Perhaps the secret of this country&#39;s success has something to do with the local addiction to one extremely fetid fish dish?
Take a few overripe pieces of cheese.
Put them in a pile of dirty and sweaty sportswear.
Leave them there for a week.
You will get the smell of rakfisk, one of the most famous Norwegian delicacies, that is repulsive to the senses.
I am in a small town called Fagernes, three hours from Oslo.
Scenic views all around covered with snow. It is very beautiful, but an indestructible characteristic smell is poured into the air.
Rakfisk is a trout sprinkled with salt and wandered in the water for up to a year, depending on what kind of darling you need to achieve.
As dusk falls and it gets colder, crowds of Norwegians gather for a festival in Fagernes dedicated to this very, shall we say, exciting dish.
&quot;It&#39;s eaten raw and washed down with a shot of aquavit, the local caraway vodka,&quot; explains Havard Halvarsen, a local fireman and part-time &quot;Rakfi general&quot; who runs the festival.
All around us, people are eating fish cut into small cubes and washing it down with large portions of alcohol.
&quot;Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk,&quot; says Havard.
This drink is able to kill the smell.
I&#39;m trying a couple of pieces.
If you manage to carry a piece under your nose, then everything is not so bad - not much different from a portion of sushi that you carried with you on the bus for a long time.
Rakfisk is a Norwegian product from a completely different time, the time of poverty, when, even before the advent of refrigerators, fish was soaked in hermetically sealed barrels of salt water in the fall.
Then, in late winter, when the fish had already fermented well and thoroughly, it was taken out and, having muffled the perception with alcohol, was eaten.
Even in the memory of the past generation, the fact that thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work and emigrate, mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants who are attracted here by jobs, high salaries and a developed social security system.
Residents of Sweden (an old rival, and not so long ago, a much more prosperous neighbor) come here en masse to work.
Rakfisk is perceived as a kind of important symbol, an indispensable, albeit somewhat stinking element of Norway&#39;s past.
This is one of the most expensive local dishes.
On the other hand, everything is expensive here - a small glass of beer or a sandwich will set you back £9 ($14).
Norway rarely appears in world news, and most of the country&#39;s inhabitants seem to be fine with that.
People here are still reluctant to mention the name of Anders Breivik, the right-wing racist and extremist who shot and killed 77 men, women and children last year.
Without mentioning his name, the attack is called &quot;what happened on July 22.&quot;
It is very difficult for Norwegians to believe that in their peaceful country one of their fellow citizens was capable of such atrocities and murders.
Norway&#39;s current prosperity is based on the growth (since the early seventies) of one of the largest oil and gas industries in the world.
&quot;But oil is not the only reason for our prosperity,&quot; says Anna, our waitress, serving trays of aged rakfisk, a woman with long blond hair and striking blue eyes, the epitome of Nordic prosperity.
We are such a people - as you call it - reasonable.
Like most Norwegians, she speaks excellent English.
We don&#39;t like to show off, we&#39;re not boastful.
Norway is very careful with its oil - most of the income of the oil and gas industry is invested in a special fund created for the benefit of future generations.
In the years leading up to the global financial crisis, when everyone was throwing away money they didn&#39;t have, Norway carefully calculated all the costs.
&quot;As long as you can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, that&#39;s enough for happiness,&quot; says Anna.
&quot;And there&#39;s rakfisk,&quot; she adds with a carefree laugh.
I&#39;m standing in the snow in line for some food - I&#39;ve had enough rakfisk.
Here is a hamburger with elk meat - this is certainly exotic, delicious juicy meat.
But in the evening we are waiting for even more of the same fish with an unforgettable smell.
My hotel hosts a special Rakfisk Dinner, during which visitors vote to determine the best or perhaps the most flavorful fish.
There is a live TV broadcast showing the presenter in a bow tie, surrounded by plates of rakfisk.
It&#39;s like the Eurovision Song Contest.
&quot;So, Tor-Jurgen, what grade did you give for the best fish there in your mountains?&quot;
&quot;Yes, Howard, here&#39;s our estimate&quot;....
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls out of their chair, possibly over the aquavit.
Or maybe just inhaling the smell of this fish.
Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto has a tough start to his career.
As newly elected Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to take a look at the challenges he will face and the mixed expectations of his country&#39;s population.
Traffic in Mexico City is now in a particularly deplorable state.
The city is congested at the best of times, and steel barriers have been erected since Monday, cutting off several key highways to the capital and causing havoc on the roads.
However, this was not done to prevent people from getting to work from the suburbs, but to prevent protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, the new head of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, will put on the presidential sling and take over the reins of the country.
He has a difficult task ahead of him.
Mexico has done well under the outgoing Felipe Calderón administration, but the country is mired in a war on drugs that has claimed about 60,000 lives in six years.
&quot;My government declares to the people of Mexico its readiness to fight violence,&quot; Mr. Peña Nieto told US President Barack Obama earlier this week in the Oval Office of the White House.
I&#39;m going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve this goal.
Prior to these announcements alongside the President of the United States, Mr. Peña Nieto&#39;s political career developed as governor of his home state of Mexico City.
In his homeland, in a densely populated and vast state surrounding the capital of the country, opinions about the new leader were divided.
Straightforward person
In the idyllic town of Valle de Bravo, for example, he is fondly remembered.
Residents credit him with the revival of tourism, the development of the resort sector and the creation of infrastructure.
The city can be reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Peña Nieto, which are very different from the pothole roads that were previously in this place.
Plaques with his name hang on the modern building of the sports center and on the impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
&quot;We pin our hopes on him for real and serious change,&quot; says his friend and political ally Gabriel Olvera Hernandez, a state congressman for Peña Nieto&#39;s Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI).
We look forward to the real and decisive changes that our country desperately needs, primarily in the areas of security and economic development.
After 81 years in power, the PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12-year absence from the presidential palace of Los Pinos, the party has high hopes for Enrique Peña Nieto.
In addition, he refutes the accusations of lack of content that the opposition has put forward to the new president.
He is very straightforward and very dedicated to bringing his vision of the country&#39;s future to life.
This is an excellent statesman, and, above all, a person who knows how to listen.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea of the former governor.
The municipality of Nezahualcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Nesa, is the most striking contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden under highway overpasses, it is, in many ways, a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also the harsh nature of this metropolis.
Troops were brought in earlier this year to quell drug gangs in these areas; and violence against women is particularly acute here.
In a wasteland near a vast dump, only in the last two years, several dozen bodies of murdered women have been discovered.
More than a thousand women were killed in Mexico State during Mr. Peña Nieto&#39;s governorship, far more than in the infamous violent city of Ciudad Juarez, which has become a household name when it comes to killing innocent women.
Mr. Peña Nieto&#39;s opponents say that, at best, he could be said to have failed to deal with the problem of killing women during his term as governor.
At worst, his administration is accused of completely ignoring the problem.
Irinea Buendía, a resident of a concrete house similar to most of the houses in this dilapidated area, struggles to hold back her tears as she shows me pictures of her late daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her boyfriend killed her.
&quot;When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed beforehand,&quot; Ms Buendia recalls.
There were signs that she had been beaten and her body was already stiff.
Mariana&#39;s mother retells the story, and her daughter&#39;s portrait looks down on us from the wall, where it hangs next to a crucifix with just one word: justice.
This, they say, was denied to this family.
“State officials treated me like an old gossip, a disgruntled troublemaker.
They want people to just take everything they say and keep quiet.
But this is wrong, it is impossible, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings around,&quot; she says.
Wearing the presidential baldric on Saturday, President Peña Nieto will take on a heavy responsibility with her.
Over the past six years, tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crime, and the new president has pledged to make addressing the issue a priority during his term.
&quot;Hopefully he will be exactly the same president that he was governor,&quot; says Olvera, a PRI congressman from Valle de Bravo.
However, this is precisely what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nessa fear most.
Bradley Manning did not complain about the mistreatment, the prosecution says.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning&#39;s claims of poor detention conditions.
During the hearing, increased attention was paid to Manning&#39;s stay in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning&#39;s conditions of detention were cruel.
A private in the US Army is accused of stealing several thousand secret documents.
On Friday, the prosecution tried to show that Pvt. Bradley Manning, charged with the biggest leak of classified material in US history, failed to take multiple opportunities to file a complaint about the mistreatment he said he endured while in military prison.
During cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, Attorney-General Major Ashden Fane stated that records of Manning&#39;s weekly visits by prison officials during his nine months in Quantico, Virginia contained no complaints of mistreatment.
Cross-examination in defense of Manning&#39;s motion to dismiss Manning&#39;s case on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and sufficient punishment in themselves took place the day after Manning stated that while in custody he intended to commit suicide .
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet by WikiLeaks.
The WikiLeaks resource has not confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
At Friday&#39;s hearing, Attorney Fein reviewed with Manning the reports filed following administration visits to Manning while he was in Quantico Prison, where he was held under high-security conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Attorney Fane asked Friday about the reports, Manning admitted that he felt &quot;excellent&quot; in his treatment of himself by the prison administration and &quot;very professionally organized.&quot;
The reports reviewed do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manning was asked directly about the conditions of his detention, Fein claims.
Manning responded that he had expressed verbal concerns about these issues and that visiting administration officials had discussed the issues with him and stated that they would be dealt with, but did not put it in writing.
&quot;They wrote down &#39;no problems&#39; (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn&#39;t mean I didn&#39;t bring it up in the conversation,&quot; says Manning.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he did not complain about his mistreatment in January 2011 during a panel meeting that considered suicidal intent, which he expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting, he wanted to have his &quot;injury prevention&quot; regime lifted and the conditions of his imprisonment softened.
Military officials explained that the restricted regime of confinement - a level lower than that of supervised suicide prevention - was put in place for the protection of the prisoner as well as for the safety of others.
&quot;I wanted to let the administration know that I&#39;m fine so that they can lift the injury prevention regime ... so that my standard of living improves, from my point of view,&quot; Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to a prison at the naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had suicidal thoughts in Kuwait and that he once passed out due to extreme heat.
He explained that it is psychologically very difficult when you are not allowed to know how your fate is decided and what is happening in the outside world.
&quot;My world has shrunk to Camp Arifjan, to the size of my prison,&quot; Manning said on Thursday.
&quot;I thought I would die in this cage.&quot;
While in Quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in the small cell - at least 21 hours, and often even more than 23 hours a day - all alone.
Manning reports that he was only allowed to keep a mattress, a blanket, flip flops, a few pieces of clothing, and glasses.
He says that he tried to move, as sleeping or even just lying down during the daytime was against the rules.
According to Manning, while sleeping, his eyes were constantly hit by light penetrating from outside the cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he rolled over in bed at night, then, according to him, he was woken up and forced to roll over on his back.
Manning&#39;s lawyer filed a formal objection to Manning&#39;s mistreatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
Also on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about a statement he made during Thursday&#39;s testimony that after being forced to sleep naked in his cell at Quantico one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates. at the morning check.
Manning stated that he was not able to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
When questioned by the judge on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard&#39;s order that he should throw in a blanket to cover himself with, but admitted that no one had directly ordered him to throw it.
On Thursday, Manning said he was forced to sleep naked the previous night because of his attempt to show an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reported that he told the officer that he could have used the elastic of his underpants or flip flops to injure himself, but did not.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, slippers and glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers are hoping that the judge will at least take into account what he went through while incarcerated and significantly reduce his sentence if Manning is found guilty by a military court due to start hearing his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to ask Manning to plead guilty to lesser crimes and challenge the other charges as excessive.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend, with the prosecution expected to insist that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held at Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the detention of detainees with the maximum strict regime.
Manning&#39;s charges include aiding an adversary, unlawfully facilitating public disclosure on the Internet, transmitting national defense information, and stealing government property or documents.
If he is convicted on all counts of the indictment, he could face life imprisonment.
My National Identity Crisis is a Mexican-American story.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who leave because they remind the people of the country of difficult times.
Rubén Navarette believes American Mexicans are torn between two cultures.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrivals corridor, approached the border control area, and froze in place.
The signs indicated two queues: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the second for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California and have been called Mexican all my life.
It&#39;s just a convention, like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish and my friends in New York call themselves Italian.
Later, I settled on the complicated &quot;Mexican American&quot; design.
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather&#39;s homeland, there was no need for conventional names or complex structures.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask or answer questions.
But my vocabulary is poorer than that of native speakers, and I can&#39;t get rid of my American accent.
So I took out my American passport and got in line for the Extranjeros.
I was reminded of this story a few days ago when newly elected Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto visited the White House and met with President Obama.
On the agenda were issues familiar to the meetings of the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Peña Nieto spoke eagerly of the rise of the Mexican economy, which would now just as well allow Mexicans to stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the US and Canada and create a kind of North American trading bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Peña Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and old grievance issue.
Most Americans never thought about the fact that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders at gunpoint to give up half of their territory.
But Mexicans think in centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events everywhere.
Therefore, as soon as any US statesman utters even a word of criticism towards Mexico, complaints are immediately heard in the press and among the elite of Mexican society that the Americans encroach on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are filled with militancy.
Mexico&#39;s relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States is the most difficult.
Do you want to talk about resentment?
They are enough.
There are winners and losers in Mexico, people who find opportunities in this country and those who don&#39;t.
There are so many people of Mexican origin in Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio for one reason only: at some point in their family history, someone - a father or grandfather - did not have the opportunity to fulfill himself in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often they were Mexicans of a certain type - swarthy, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants and we remember this.
In Mexico it is seen differently.
Today, our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we went to good schools and got good jobs, but we must not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confused and unclear, but we know which country to consider as our own.
USA.
In addition, we know that the majority of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We answer them the same.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us like second class people, like fake Mexicans.
We don&#39;t speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico aren&#39;t strong enough.
Our very existence for them is explained by failures.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they would not have left.
We would not now find ourselves behind a silk curtain, having found a well-fed life in the USA, but having lost spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and moved legally to the US as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain tensions between real Mexicans and Mexican Americans - Mexicans understand their national identity more clearly, and Mexican Americans are hurt by this.
She is a US citizen and believes she belongs to both of these countries.
At the same time, many of the Mexican Americans I know don&#39;t feel like they belong to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also love Bruce Springsteen.
When you get the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico we are Americans.
And in the US they call us Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relations weren&#39;t complicated enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican Americans to serve as a kind of ambassador for Mexico and represent her interests in the US.
We could tell our American friends what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah of course.
Nothing will come of it.
Too many hurts in the past.
And given the gap between the rich and the poor, rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not think this country is all that beautiful.
Sorry, but deal with this yourself, amigos.
And this is fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will also have to accept the fact that some Mexican Americans are still offended by how their relatives were treated in Mexico just recently. .
Yeah.
We probably have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
Ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis possible in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed pushes the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
There are familiar, meaningless disputes about who started it first; many buildings turned into ruins; over 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis were killed; For the first time during the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip fell in the vicinity of the Israeli capital Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that the Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly mired in their age-old conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated in different ways, but the events of the &quot;Arab spring&quot; swirled in a rebellious storm many established realities, and the Palestinians and Israelis did not manage to stay away from the whirlwind that shook the region.
Perhaps as a result, their fight will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons that give hope for a way out of this deadly impasse.
War without winners
At first glance, the current situation does not give grounds for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on November 21 is implemented, this week&#39;s clashes have only strengthened the positions of security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist movement Hamas, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will say that they forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the leaders of the group were destroyed, and 1.7 million inhabitants are blocked in one of the most densely populated and problematic corners of our planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing in popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well come to the conclusion that time is on their side.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new powerful and wealthy friends.
A resurgent regional leader Turkey, once Israel&#39;s closest Muslim ally, has come out in support of Hamas; Qatar, one of the richest and fastest growing states in the Persian Gulf, followed suit.
Triumphant Hamas supporters claim an Islamist crescent around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, ruled by the paramilitary group Hezbollah, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to topple Bashar al-Assad, and on to Jordan, where the king&#39;s power is threatened by allies. Hamas.
The most significant shift in the balance of power in the region has occurred on Israel&#39;s southern borders, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where the Muslim Brotherhood&#39;s influence has grown stronger under President Mohammed Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was ousted in 2011, was a secular dictator with little support for Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, by contrast, is an organization much like Hamas, and its leaders are more populist.
In future diplomatic alignments, Hamas could become a significant player whose voice cannot be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, hardliners in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
Militarily, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli Iron Dome anti-missile system justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the missiles launched by Hamas.
Israeli citizens can sleep peacefully, at least for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the US remained true to its unchanged position; many European countries have also placed the blame for starting the latest round of violence on Hamas.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, who has largely ignored the peace process.
Although approximately 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from Gaza since 2004, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombings, in part by building a wall that extends into the West Bank, a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian states - and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions from the point of view of international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for elections scheduled for January 22 - has teamed up with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is quite comfortable.
What is the point of pandering to the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If you give them all the power in the West Bank, will they not launch rockets from there towards Israel, as their counterparts in the Gaza Strip do?
It&#39;s best to keep them behind a wall and firmly suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Perhaps the hardliners will win; however, their calculations may be refuted by the Arab Spring.
While the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere do not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
Israel&#39;s defense budget is larger than that of all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egyptian President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama for a ceasefire, is a good sign and could mark the beginning of change.
Israel, no less, must consider the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic changes take place in the Arab countries, the loss of the Palestinian right to self-determination is a time bomb that will explode sooner or later in the Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus bombing in Tel Aviv this week.
Repression is already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to pay with the growing discontent of the international community.
Both sides need external momentum
There remains the only solution that sound-minded representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper, are constantly calling for: the formation of two states and Israeli cessions of territory in exchange for security.
There remains hope, not very impressive in the short term, that the ceasefire will allow other countries to more effectively influence the parties to the conflict.
Egypt, long overdue for its decision to cut off arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, are better positioned than ever to persuade Hamas to recognize the boundaries of the Jewish state, adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the sharing of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in the recognition of a virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama also has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never submitted his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he still demonstrates an unwillingness to get involved in solving this problem.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible if there is a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the Uniform Packaging for Cigarettes Act has come into force.
Health warnings and images of diseased body parts stand out on dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
Australia&#39;s first-ever Uniform Packaging Act for cigarettes and tobacco products has gone into effect, replacing brand logos and color schemes with a dreary olive-colored box with eerie pictures of diseased body parts and images of children whose health is undermined by their parents&#39; smoking.
In addition to various pictures and inscriptions warning about the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packs, introduced without fail from this Saturday, is the names of the brands, which are printed in the same small print.
These are the most severe conditions in the world for the packaging of tobacco products.
The Australian federal government says the measure is intended to keep young people from smoking by removing the habit from fashionable status.
This decision was based on the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26, in 99 cases out of 100, never become smokers.
“It is clear that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging design,” explains Minister of Health Tanja Plibersek, referring to studies showing that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated in children with the idea of a princess. .
Australia is one of the world&#39;s lowest smoking countries, so these changes will not affect the profits of multinational corporations much, but other countries are already considering such measures.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies argue that this will only increase the share of the black market, which will sell cheap and affordable cigarettes.
&quot;This law will lead to serious consequences, different from those that were conceived by its initiators,&quot; said Scott McIntyre, a representative of British American Tobacco in Australia.
Manufacturers of counterfeit products from China and Indonesia will supply many more of these products for sale on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, new laws contribute to business growth.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family business, says demand for cigarette cases and silicone cases that hide nasty pictures on the packaging has skyrocketed (virtually from nothing) since the likes of British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost their case in the Australian High Court to challenge the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about six thousand products to wholesalers and is waiting for a new batch.
This is good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among precisely the part of the population that these measures are aimed at.
After the adoption of a series of laws in Australia that made television advertising of cigarettes and their support of sporting events illegal, as well as prohibiting sellers from displaying cigarettes in a conspicuous place, tobacco advertising has moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local businesses and websites from advertising online, but it cannot restrict overseas sites from doing so.
&quot;If you&#39;re a tobacco dealer and you&#39;re left with just this little loophole, the idea of promoting your product online is very tempting,&quot; explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes an increase in trademark reviews written by ostensibly ordinary users on social networks such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question arises - is this really the work of an ordinary citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he spared no effort and time and made a video, or is there an advertising company behind this?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco says the industry is now more busy adapting to the new rules than advertising.
The tobacco industry has even gone to such lengths as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these states are making claims under the World Trade Organization that trade has been subjected to unfair restrictions, despite the fact that trade relations of all these countries with Australia are very insignificant.
A WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tania Plibersek, the government has been discussing with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada pioneered the mandatory posting of health warning photos.
Now this rule has been adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia defiantly disobey the innovations.
These pictures don&#39;t bother me.
I just don&#39;t pay attention.
&quot;You just grab a cigarette and put the pack in your pocket,&quot; explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumor on the pack.
To be honest, the only thing that can make me quit is my little daughter.
James Yu, who runs the King of the Pack cigarette shop in Sydney&#39;s city centre, says the same packaging has made it difficult to sort items on the shelves.
&quot;It used to take me an hour to unload a new batch, but now it takes me four hours,&quot; he complains.
&quot;The government should have gone and completely banned cigarettes, then we would have said: what to do, okay, it&#39;s over, we close the store,&quot; he says, throwing his hands up.
Being bored in the world of electronic networks and constant connections is not so bad.
This Thanksgiving, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at the airport, because our plane had mechanical problems and was replaced by another plane, which we were waiting for.
Thus, I had enough time to reflect on the nature of boredom.
I won&#39;t deceive you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and books, magazines, iPhones, and even duty-free shops will not help much.
Recently, however, more and more scientists and specialists in child development have spoken out in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations, it is not so bad for us and for our children to be bored.
This forces the brain to divert to interesting related topics, which may encourage creativity.
And since in the modern world we are all constantly in front of some kind of screen, the benefits of boredom pass us by.
Maybe we need to aim for boredom?
Yes.
And at the same time no.
We&#39;ll get back to this.
I used to think, like many others, that boredom was an invention of relatively recent times, when people had more free time.
It&#39;s not, says Peter Twoy, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
&quot;In fact, boredom has a very ancient history,&quot; he says.
Latin inscriptions about boredom dating back to the first century have been found on walls in Pompeii.
However, the question of how we understand boredom remains open.
The problem, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, is that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After reviewing research on the topic and asking a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came up with the following definition: boredom is when people &quot;want but cannot do what would bring them satisfaction.&quot;
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person doesn&#39;t do something they would like to do.
When you&#39;re apathetic, you don&#39;t want to do anything.
The core of the boredom experience, he says, is &quot;disturbance of attention and associated deterioration in mood and the feeling that time is passing slowly.&quot;
Boredom can be described as very similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible connection between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the world around them and circumstances, while depressed people see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we think that we are bored, when in fact we just find it difficult to focus on something.
In their study, &quot;An Unoccupied Mind: Defining Boredom in terms of attention,&quot; published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a recording of a voice reading a magazine.
Some participants also heard the loud sounds of an irrelevant TV program playing in the next room, others heard the same sounds at a low volume, so that they could hardly be heard, and the third group listened only to the recording of the voice without an extraneous sound track.
Those participants who listened to the TV at a low volume noted that they were bored, more often than others - they had difficulty concentrating, but they did not know the reason for this and attributed it to boredom.
When we&#39;re trying to focus on a difficult or exciting task, attention interruptions can cause boredom, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of this study.
On the other hand, when we&#39;re doing something uninteresting, &quot;for example, peering down a line of products on an assembly line looking for defects, distracting music can help stave off boredom.&quot;
It is believed, he continues, that when people start swaying in a chair or doodling on a piece of paper, they do it out of boredom, but now we know that in fact, such actions simply help not to relax physically.
&quot;The study showed that children who are not prevented from fidgeting and fidgeting learn better and remember more information than children who are required to sit still,&quot; says Professor Fenske.
At some point, we all experience boredom: when a flight is delayed (as in my case), listening to a monotonous speech, watching an uninteresting movie.
However, different people show different degrees of boredom.
In the 1980s, researchers developed a &quot;boredomness scale&quot; to measure these individual characteristics.
Questions and statements are used to determine the rating on this scale, for example, &quot;A lot of what I have to do is monotonous and monotonous&quot; or &quot;I am interested in too many things, so there is not enough time for anything.&quot;
Using such questionnaires, the researchers determined that boys are more likely to be bored than girls, says Steven Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially in the presence of a variety of external stimuli.
However, in general, teenagers generally often get bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he paged nearly 400 teenagers and their parents 7-8 times a day.
He got the following results: 32% of teenagers said they were bored at school and during homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
At the same time, only 3% of parents noted that they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what similar boredom data would be now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that &quot;the peak of boredom tends to peak during adolescence,&quot; largely because children and teens aren&#39;t allowed to fully decide what they want to do.
Back to my original question: Is boredom healthy?
Sometimes not, because at its extreme, studies show it can push people into absurd and dangerous physical activities, risky gambling, or the abuse of certain substances in an attempt to get rid of boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have thought about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has devoted more than two decades to studying this problem.
&quot;This is how our brain tells us to do something else; that&#39;s boredom,&quot; says Gary Marcus, professor of psychology at New York University.
However, this very brain does not always know what exactly is best to do.
If you get bored and channel that energy into playing the guitar or experimenting with food, you will make yourself feel better.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only get better for a while, and soon it will pass.
Therefore, if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will stop being bored, but he will not learn to deal with boredom on his own or in any other way manage his time and busyness, says Professor Fenske.
&quot;And these self-regulatory skills come into play in a wide variety of situations,&quot; he says.
Your child is not only learning to occupy himself with something, he is also learning self-control in general.
I don&#39;t think boredom should be praised in any way.
However, it should not be considered something bad either.
Rather, one should learn to feel comfortable even outside the continuous flow of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees with this.
“The way we see it is that we need to get bored more often, when boredom is a very unpleasant, unquenchable desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
In fact, people tend to somehow disconnect from constant worries and just relax.
&quot;In today&#39;s world, we are used to constant over-stimulation of the senses,&quot; he says, &quot;and when silence comes, we are lost and do not know what to do.&quot;
It is not yet clear how the new marijuana legalization law will be applied in the state of Colorado
Anthony Orozco, a nineteen-year-old football player and community college student in southeastern Colorado, has been charged with a felony that will soon be perfectly legal throughout the state: possession of a small amount of marijuana and a pipe in which he smoked it.
Mr. Orosco says he was in Lamar with some friends one September and was driving across the prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer found marijuana in the car, Mr. Orozco received a subpoena for possession of drugs and possession of a drug paraphernalia—minor offenses that carry a $100 fine each—and a court date was set.
&quot;We are being treated like criminals,&quot; says Mr. Orozco.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that has been going on for weeks after the state of Colorado voted to legalize small-scale recreational marijuana use, hundreds of small court cases are decided less by law than by venue.
Marijuana misdemeanor charges are already being dropped in hundreds of cases here and in the state of Washington, which has taken a similar action.
Police stations have already stopped filing charges against people aged 21 and over for possession of small doses, which will become legal as soon as the law goes into effect in a couple of weeks.
However, in more conservative Colorado counties, prosecutors have chosen to pursue existing marijuana cases and are still prosecuting possession of the drug.
At the same time, cities from suburban Denver to the highlands of the West are voting to keep new, state-licensed marijuana stores from entering their localities.
&quot;This is moving so fast that I don&#39;t even know what to expect next,&quot; says Daniel J. Oates, police chief in the town of Aurora, east of Denver.
Regulatory officials in Washington State are also scratching their heads in puzzlement.
They will have to form rules to determine how marijuana is licensed to grow, process, distribute and sell, all of which must be done by December 1, 2013.
They say that Colorado, for better or worse, is ahead of most other states in regulating the use of marijuana, first for medical purposes and now for recreation.
&quot;Colorado has a more orderly market, so they&#39;re a good example,&quot; said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Washington State Liquor Regulatory Council.
But right now, no one can do more, Mr. Smith admits, than put forward some proposals and hope it works.
&quot;We don&#39;t have a real precedent that we can look at,&quot; he says.
The Washington state bill, called I-502, will go into effect on December 6 and will plunge the state into a state of limbo for a full year, with no state licensing system yet and legal possession of marijuana.
And there are still tricky technical issues that need to be addressed during this period, such as how to balance the state&#39;s order for &quot;adequate access&quot; to licensed marijuana with a ban on its sale within 1,000 feet of schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens. .
&quot;It will be especially difficult to locate licensed marijuana dealers in urban areas, particularly in Seattle and its suburbs,&quot; said Ben Livingston, spokesman for the recently formed Center for Marijuana Legalization Research Group.
On November 21, Police Chief Oates of Aurora sent out an email to his subordinates that the city&#39;s Attorney&#39;s Office would no longer prosecute individuals over the age of 21 for possession of small amounts of marijuana, and that the police would stop incriminating people for these violations &quot;starting from now on&quot;.
Police Chief Oates said the police will enforce the city&#39;s rules governing medical marijuana growers and prosecute illegal drug dealers and distributors.
Weld County District Attorney in northern Colorado, Ken Buck, is taking a more rigorous approach to the matter.
After voting on the bill, he said that prosecutors would continue to prosecute marijuana possession, mainly to encourage marijuana users to seek treatment.
So far, 119 individuals have been charged with possession of two or less ounces of marijuana, although many of them are charged with other violations.
&quot;It is our institution&#39;s duty to prosecute acts that are considered criminal at the time they are committed,&quot; Mr. Buck said in a statement.
Reaction was mixed even in places like rural Mesa, where voters rejected a proposal to legalize marijuana.
Police in Grand Junction, the largest city in the county, are no longer prosecuting adults for possession of small amounts of drugs.
District Attorney Pete Houtzinger supported the decision, but also decided not to drop the charges in the already open marijuana possession cases.
&quot;I think it&#39;s our responsibility to enforce the law until it changes,&quot; he says.
While 55% of Colorado residents who voted supported the decision, getting recreational marijuana into the state and legal system will not be easy.
And the conflicting reactions of residents across the state exposed the ambiguity of the attitude of local authorities to the state&#39;s experiment with marijuana.
&quot;District attorneys have a cultural barrier to this,&quot; said Sean McAllister, a Denver marijuana attorney and local spokesman for the National Marijuana Law Reform Organization.
&quot;They&#39;ve been persecuting people for this for so long that they can&#39;t really come to terms with the fact that it&#39;s no longer a crime,&quot; he says.
Colorado and Washington - the first states to treat a small amount of marijuana the same way as alcohol - are destined to become a nationwide experimental field for testing the very idea of drug legalization.
Legalization advocates and state officials plan to expand the territory of the legalized trade, but at the same time they are cautiously waiting for instructions from the federal government, which still plans to consider the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Advocates of marijuana legalization are hoping that the Justice Department will give in on this issue.
Despite several high-profile arrests of drug dealers and patients for medical marijuana use, the federal government has largely approved medical marijuana sales in Colorado, Washington, and 16 other states.
Drug Enforcement Bureau agents are unlikely to break into homes to confiscate a small bag of marijuana, but they are unlikely to turn a blind eye to state-regulated recreational marijuana shops that are allowed under the new law, said Kevin A. Sabet, former counselor for drug control in the Obama administration.
Some cities in Colorado did not wait for the actions of the federal authorities.
Even before the presidential election, some local governments approved a moratorium on the opening of new marijuana stores that would not be able to open for less than a year anyway.
Last week, Montrose, a city in the western part of the state, put forward a six-month marijuana ban that is likely to be approved next week.
&quot;We don&#39;t want to be in a position where we give someone a license and then it causes serious problems at the federal level,&quot; says Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
Our city voted against this amendment.
And now we have a contradiction between the results of the local vote and what the state voted for.
There are still a lot of unresolved questions.
Petronella Wyatt: I was kicked out of Oxford for being a Conservative.
The persecution of university students for their views did not begin today.
For as long as I can remember, I have always dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and elder brother studied at Oxford and described it as the best educational institution in the world, a modern analogue of the ancient symposium, laying the two foundations of civilization - freethinking and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of studying history at Worcester College, Oxford University in the late eighties, I packed my bags and left, which resulted in the first real scandal of my life.
My father broke down and cried.
Friends were bewildered.
The Evening Standard claimed that I dropped out of college because I didn&#39;t like my classmates having sex in the next room.
Writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I left because I had to drink from chipped cups.
It really wasn&#39;t all that funny.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was systematically harassed and intimidated.
Not at all because of my rather unusual name or the fact that I went to a private school.
I was hounded for only one reason, and in this glorious cradle of enlightenment, it looked like real barbarism and blind fanaticism: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a famous adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I myself was a supporter of the conservatives.
You ask, why remember this now?
According to recent reports, a new generation of center-right students are being targeted in the same way.
This institutionalized and ever-increasing hatred of conservative students at Oxford is so strong that last week a group of such students demanded the same protection for their rights as that given to disabled, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives from Corpus Christi College&#39;s student club in Cambridge say they are &quot;often actively sequestered, personally attacked and made to feel like unwanted guests&quot; because of their political views.
They want to add an additional representative to the college&#39;s equal rights committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation has only been exacerbated by the recently released BBC 2 documentary on student politics, Wonderland: The Young, the Smart and the Right, which portrayed conservatives as eccentrics and neo-Nazis.
The film featured Joe Cook, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association, driving a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a silver-headed cane.
At other universities, conservative students complain that they are being made &quot;scapegoats for tuition increases.&quot;
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, said in an interview with a Sunday newspaper that “there is a growing left-leaning bias in the university environment.
People who don&#39;t even know us think we are impudent and violent children of rich parents with impunity.&quot;
Samuel Roberts, 21, a history student at Corpus Christi College, where the protections were petitioned for, calls the atmosphere &quot;uncomfortable&quot;, while Stephanie Cherill, 19, the new president of the Oxford University Conservative Association, says the attitude of the student club to bearers of right-of-centre views has deteriorated significantly.
&quot;This is a threat both to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion and simply to the normal life of the members of the club,&quot; she says.
For the first few weeks at Oxford, I was not only in the minority, I was alone.
I entered there in September 1986, a timid and shy eighteen year old girl.
Oxford was feverish with hatred for the Conservative Party.
The year before, the university voted to strip former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree due to higher education budget cuts.
In such an atmosphere, even the Stalinists would be uncomfortable.
During the first days of the freshman week, when students get to know each other and the teachers, for the first time I had a sense of what lay ahead of me.
I did not yet know that the teachers not only turned a blind eye to the persecution of conservative students, but also took part in it with pleasure.
Political issues - a miners&#39; strike, privatization, and the government&#39;s refusal to impose sanctions on South Africa&#39;s apartheid government - crept through the wood-paneled auditorium walls.
In my first seminar, I needed to translate an eighteenth-century French text into English, and I was unprepared for what followed.
&quot;Miss Wyatt,&quot; said the teacher, the late Harry Pitt, &quot;please translate the first paragraph.&quot;
The text was given to me with difficulty, I stumbled.
Harry Pitt was a very bilious man with a cake-like face.
&quot;The Thatcherists don&#39;t learn French on principle, or do they just lack the brains?&quot; - he asked.
The other students giggled.
I had tears in my eyes.
&quot;I suggest you take some early French lessons in your spare time, unless you&#39;re very busy moving around,&quot; Pitt grumbled.
I returned to my room completely miserable.
That evening in college I sat at dinner alone; then someone patted me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year student in the English department, who introduced himself as a member of the University Conservative Association.
&quot;I know who you are,&quot; he said amiably.
- Unfortunately, the situation is as follows:
anyone who is suspected of sympathizing with the conservatives will be mocked.
It&#39;s not easy for me myself, but in your case they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it will be more difficult for you.
Most Conservative freshmen pretend to be Labor.&quot;
Later, at the local pub, I cowardly tried to be hypocritical.
I insisted that I did not agree with everything Margaret Thatcher said.
The ploy failed.
A freshman in philosophy, politics and economics, who himself studied at Eton, said: &quot;You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You are contagious.&quot;
Other students took up his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
&quot;How do conservatives have sex?&quot; One of them asked.
&quot;They hit each other, don&#39;t they?&quot;
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the decriminalization in the sixties.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life in Oxford?
Or will I have to meet like-minded people only under the cover of night?
Will I be forced to become a Labor Party and hide my true beliefs?
The next three years began to seem like hell, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only professor in my college who was openly conservative was Norman Stone, professor of modern history.
He was hated not only for belonging to the Conservatives, but also for being Thatcher&#39;s foreign policy adviser and one of her speechwriters.
He hardly showed up in college.
He despised him for his provinciality, pettiness and adherence to the Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997, he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
&quot;You won&#39;t be happy here,&quot; he told me.
I began to travel to Oxford from my parents&#39; house in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and open-minded friends in the capital.
I told my father that I hate Oxford and explained the reason.
He didn&#39;t believe me.
During his studies in the forties, any political views were accepted there.
&quot;But it&#39;s the best university in the world,&quot; he said plaintively.
“They can’t do that, only not in the city of dormant spiers ...
Even my communist friends have always behaved impeccably.&quot;
His wet eyes clouded over.
&quot;Don&#39;t make hasty decisions.
I&#39;m sure it&#39;s just a joke.
You will break my heart if you drop out of university.&quot;
I was exhausted from the constant trips to London and my emotional defenses were weakening.
My friend, also a conservative, succumbed to the pressure and renounced his beliefs.
During a seminar the following week, when another history professor quite seriously called me an &quot;enemy of the people,&quot; I decided to do the same.
In my heart, burning with shame, I admitted that &quot;I was brainwashed by my parents&quot; and called them &quot;old fools.&quot;
The break was short lived.
The final nail in the coffin of my career at Oxford was my father&#39;s.
At the time, he wrote two columns every week for publications owned by Rupert Murdoch.
My door was locked.
I did not come out, and five minutes later my pursuers surrendered.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and took the first train to London.
I never returned.
You can call me a crybaby and a rag.
But at the age of eighteen, no one should be the object of such anger and intimidation in an educational institution.
It is all the more sad because it was Oxford, which not only produced fourteen Tory prime ministers, but to this day hides behind the undeserved reputation of a university that values equality and free thought.
&quot;Valentino prefers elegance to glory&quot;
About the exhibition &quot;Valentino: Master of Sewing&quot;, which opened this week in London, ABC talks with Nati Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemitsa and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, the former residence of Queen Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this during the opening of &quot;Valentino: Master of Sewing&quot;, a triumphant retrospective exhibition that brings together more than 130 haute couture dresses created by his &quot;house&quot; over the past 50 years.
&quot;I love this palace,&quot; he says in his unique Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of a story whose only character is &quot;il signore&quot; Garavani, but it could not have been written without his eminent clients.
Valentino has always felt fascinated by the rare and distant world of the nobility.
The first room of this exhibition, open until March 3, is replete with personal letters and photographs signed by the most distinguished aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, including Marie-Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino displays these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from a modest tailor in the northern Italian city of Voghera to an idol of the international &quot;elite&quot;.
There is nothing wrong with being in love with the royal court.
&quot;At least they don&#39;t snuff out their cigarette butts on your gorgeous carpet like some great pop stars do,&quot; says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemitsa.
In the 60s and 70s we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a peerless host and welcomes guests with generosity and elegance.
