The hardest job in the world: miners from Kawah Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk life and limb by dragging 70 kilograms of sulfur to the top of the volcano along steep rocky paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, while others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who make a living mining sulfur in the Kawah Ijen volcano, located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Anto descends to the very bottom of the crater, where sulfur dioxide rising from the depths of the Earth solidifies on contact with air.
Having broken off huge pieces of sulfur, the total weight of which can reach 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, heels the baskets on his shoulders and carries them up the steep rocky road.
The summit of the volcano, which is 2,386 meters high, is only 250 meters, but it takes more than 40 minutes for exhausted loaders to climb at a snail&#39;s pace, struggling to maintain balance and carefully groping for the road so as not to stumble and fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened to a tourist from France who fell off the cliffs of Kawah Ijen a few years ago.
Miners from Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulfur they mine
Once at the top, they make their way between tourists who take pictures of them, as if they were monkeys from a circus and, wearily carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometers to the scales, which the mining company has placed a little higher, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
We are talking about PT Kandy Ngrimbi, an enterprise that has been exploiting this volcano since 1960 and, better not to say, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 euro cents) for every kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to petrochemical industries, because this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
&quot;Because carrying 70 kilograms is the norm, we earn about 46,000 rupees (€3.8) per walk,&quot; explains Anto, who usually does three daily transfers.
He spends three hours on each of them and feels overwhelmed at the end, but they allow him to save 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
Although it seems like a meager amount for such an inhuman effort, it is three times what he would earn in the field.
&quot;Daily wages for miners are very high by local standards, where coffee pickers are paid Rs 15,000 (€1.2) per day and the average monthly salary is Rs 2 million (€167),&quot; explains a loader who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali. .
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the plot was not so difficult, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a good reason, which in Indonesia is as crushing as sulfur: &quot;I married a girl from Bali, where there are only Hindus, and brought her to Java to convert to Islam.&quot;
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, constantly coughs, and has watery eyes due to toxic gases.
At 27, Anto spent three years risking his life in Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur was already beginning to take its toll despite wearing a mask and special goggles.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly, and has watery eyes due to the toxic gases the volcano releases.
This is the price he must pay to achieve his dream.
&quot;I&#39;ll work for another two years because I want to open a store or learn Spanish or French,&quot; he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this pleasant and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, a waiter or a porter at a hotel, but instead he does the job of a mule.
Sharing a dirty wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning, because sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns into blue and glitters in the darkness.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends into the crater, lighting his way with a small flashlight connected to his helmet, which he himself bought with his own money.
About 400 porters carry baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano.
Despite high profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to porters who work for their own account and with such hardships.
In fact, they don&#39;t even get a fraction of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) photography fee that, along with the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) entrance ticket, the guards of this reserve charge from tourists who come to photograph the volcano and his mule people.
&quot;This job is for the cattle, not the people,&quot; says Badrusin, a 42-year-old stocky porter who has spent three decades on Kawah Ijen since leaving college.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, he says he will endure working &quot;as much as he can&quot; because he needs money to educate his three children, aged 18 to 10.
Won&#39;t retire, die here because the volcano is my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and burns the eyes, when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in dense plumes of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardy that not one complains of their serious illnesses ... more serious, obviously, than their usual problems with breathing, arthrosis, pain in the knees and ulcers on the shoulders, which were deformed under the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unaynik can now only lift 50 kilograms at his 53 years old.
Every day, he and his comrades carry 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which are transported by three trucks to a warehouse in Tamansari, overcoming a distance of 18 kilometers along a narrow path through the thickets.
“I won’t retire, I’ll die here, because the volcano is my whole life,” Unaynik says, opening his mouth wide, which is missing several teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, aged 30, also works as a sulfur carrier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest jobs in the world: what the human mules of Kawah Ijen do.
Singapore is looking for children to save the economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress and housing and education prices for not having children.
&quot;Singapore&#39;s population needs to grow.&quot;
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, let&#39;s fulfill our civic duty and create life!
It may seem unbelievable that these lines are part of an advertisement for mints, but in spite of this - or perhaps because of this - this video became a hit on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
