Many of these ideas may have been creative but didn&#39;t necessarily work.
So we thought, why don&#39;t we do the most creative thing we can to solve this problem, which is rapping?
1.2 children
Who doesn&#39;t take it so lightly is the government of Singapore.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to inspire citizens to have more children.
The State Parent and Couple Package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave, and provides tax relief.
But all this is of low efficiency.
Singapore is a wealthy and high-tech city state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservative leadership and strict social control.
Singapore&#39;s birth rate, according to its National Population Authority, is currently at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was below 2 - what is known as the replacement percentage - was in 1976.
So why don&#39;t Singaporeans have more children?
Tang Wei Ming, director of the National Population Administration&#39;s Couples and Families Policy Division, says the reason is &quot;improved education&quot; and &quot;a wider range of career opportunities.&quot;
&quot;This has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities beyond getting married and starting a family,&quot; she explains.
These changes in social norms contribute to an increase in the number of bachelors and the postponement of marriage and childbearing, resulting in a decrease in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, immigration policies that aim to boost immigration to counter population declines are causing resentment among the local population.
There are websites in Singapore where thinly disguised xenophobia thrives against many new immigrants, especially the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and unwilling to integrate.
Rising immigration is also seen as one of the reasons Singapore&#39;s ruling party had its worst election result since independence last year.
After the election, there was an attempt to solve the problem with quotas and higher taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While falling birth rates are having a known impact on a nation&#39;s economic growth, tax revenues, healthcare spending and immigration policy, the example of Singapore is also beginning to have some unexpected consequences.
The government is making efforts not to build so many small houses.
For example, it began to affect the real estate sector.
The City Development Guide has moved to control the number of small apartments, known as &quot;shoeboxes&quot;, that can be built in certain areas of the city.
This 46 square meter apartment is selling very well.
However, there is a perception that they can encourage bachelor living and de-incentivize developers who want to build large family homes.
But Lim Yu Sun, CEO of homebuilder EL Developers, says their &quot;shoeboxes&quot; sell much faster than larger ones.
They are more popular, in the sense that such apartments sell out in a few days, even weeks, faster than larger apartments.
As a result, our cash receipts are increasing.
However, he acknowledges that the new rules provide clearer guidance for developers who were previously stymied if they wanted to offer too many small apartments in a project.
Too overstressed
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step towards boosting the nation&#39;s birth rate, after talking to Singaporeans who work in the center&#39;s financial district, it doesn&#39;t seem like they will have much effect.
&quot;People are very stressed, housing is expensive, as well as education, and because of this, many people are putting it off,&quot; says the young manager.
Other people may have children.
&quot;But it&#39;s important for me to have my own money and time,&quot; says another young man in his 20s.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and the cost of housing and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, no matter how hard the government tries to encourage its citizens to have children, when it comes to childbearing, the Singaporeans have the last word.
Personal offline - personal online
