UNASUR Summit Ends Without Lima Declaration Released
The VI presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, announced earlier and theoretically signed by the seven mandatory participants.
Efe repeatedly tried to get access to the document signed at the 6th Ordinary Meeting of the Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, however, sources from the Office and the Presidential Administration indicated on the main page that it would be handed over after closing, but then confirmed that at some point it would be published on the web website of the Peruvian government.
When asked about the text, they indicated that the content was laid out by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief press statements.
Journalists&#39; access to information about the Summit was limited all the time.
All that was broadcast during the day, in the press room, was a silent video of the Presidential Assembly with the message &quot;Closed meeting, no sound.&quot;
The little information that circulated among the reporters was relayed by the press secretaries of some of the UNASUR governments present at the meeting, but not the Peruvian one.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of participating presidents, which angered hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the administration of the President of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the &quot;final declaration&quot; of the summit, but this is Humala&#39;s statement, and not the official document that ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the III South American and Arab Summit (ASPA), and at that time, despite the fact that the press insistently demanded it, the so-called Lima Declaration, which was previously announced, was also not circulated.
On the official ASPA website, you can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to ensure that transmission systems were provided for all journalists, but they limited the receipt of information as much as possible.
The summit also ended with the joint decision of Chile and Peru to accept the verdict of the Hague Court, which will settle the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, gathered at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which is starting to hear statements from both sides in The Hague on Monday, as part of the accusation that Lima has brought against Santiago.
&quot;We will respect and implement a decision that will clarify the differences that we are currently presenting to this international court,&quot; said Humala, next to his Chilean counterpart.
&quot;Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful settlement of differences, pacts and international tribunals,&quot; Piñera added, and greeted Humala with a handshake against the backdrop of the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will submit to the International Court of Justice comes immediately after Colombia protested this week the Bogotá Pact, under which it accepted submission to the verdicts of this international court after the decision on maritime borders with Nicaragua, which it considered erroneous.
The summit took place in the absence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Christina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose UNASUR membership has been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former president, Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was responsible for opening discussions in the morning and closing the summit a little after noon Lima time.
The head of state read the final document, in which he said that 16 agreements were adopted and directions of action were approved for 31 projects among South American countries, the amount of the proposed investment was $17 billion.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR countries will take &quot;important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding residency agreements.&quot;
He said actions are being taken to improve &quot;collaboration in the fight against citizen insecurity and organized transnational crime, action to increase the availability of medicines, low-cost Internet access in all corners of South America, and address the risks of natural disasters in a cumulative and effective manner.&quot;
As Europe is in crisis, &quot;(Latin America&#39;s) economic unification should not have a triumphant basis, but should serve to expand our manufacturing base and envision a better future for our cities,&quot; Humala added.
&quot;We have decided to privilege a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connectivity of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas ... uniting our countries and forming new economic patterns,&quot; the Peruvian president said in a read message.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were related to Peru, and limited to transverse axes in its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide more details.
The final document also touched upon the political situation in Paraguay.
&quot;We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to re-join the Union of South American Nations,&quot; from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, to be united, and to have good relations among neighbors, was another theme highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before entering the regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to negotiate in a respectful manner on the maritime dispute resulting from the verdict of the international court contested by Bogotá.
&quot;The day after tomorrow (Saturday) I will probably meet with President Daniel Ortega,&quot; Santos said.
&quot;We will review all these ways, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua,&quot; he stressed.
&quot;With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we will handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,&quot; Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City, where they are scheduled to attend the inauguration of the country&#39;s new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also within the framework of the summit, the bloc&#39;s defense ministers tentatively met to approve the Action Plan for 2013, which aims to strengthen dialogue and unanimity on the issue of protecting the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although participation of the last of the countries is suspended.
Peru has an interim presidency in the regional bloc.
