AIDS deaths today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was announced that he had tested positive for AIDS.
“It was like I was stunned,” he recalls that difficult moment, despite all the doctor’s tact.
The young man hid this from his family.
Deciding to cope with the disease on his own, he wanted to learn about it as much as possible. And his efforts paid off - he has already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the &quot;oldest&quot; patients in the HIV department of the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he arrived in 1994 after overcoming many obstacles.
He has been living with a diagnosis of human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years. In the early 90s, it would have been hard to believe - there were too few treatment options then, too little was known about the disease, too biased towards the sick.
So, even the director of the clinic of the Mexican Institute of Social Security did not want to say goodbye to him, &quot;because he had a cut.&quot;
In other words, in those days, having AIDS was a death sentence.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do so without compromising quality of life.
However, unaware of their illness, many people still come in when the virus has already taken its toll, &quot;depleted&quot; their immune systems and they are suffering from opportunistic infections.
31 years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, at least after the first reported cases, &quot;the great achievement at the moment is that the survival of the patient who begins treatment on time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same,&quot; said the head of the HIV department. HCG, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, citing that this information was confirmed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectionist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva explained that since 2008 scientists have come to the conclusion that AIDS is not a death sentence, but life expectancy and quality of life depend on the degree of damage to the immune system present in patients at the start of diagnosis, with a better life expectancy of life in those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years with 200 CD4 counts, and up to 50 years when 500 CD4 counts are reported.
Simply put, the above means that someone who receives an HIV-positive diagnosis at age 25, according to these terms, &quot;maintaining control, will be able to live without problems until the age of 75,&quot; he explained.
To appreciate this progress, remember that the life expectancy of Mexicans today averages 76 years.
Although mortality has dropped significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying of AIDS has dropped from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that since the advent of AIDS, 60 percent of patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths had already been registered by May this year; however, it is claimed that there has been universal access to antiretrovirals since 2005.
Why are there still deaths?
- Personally, it seems to me that the problem is not in access to treatment.
This is how I imagine it, this is how things are in our hospital.
For at least the last 12 years, we have not had a shortage of medicines, the problem is that patients come very late, because they do not know about their infected condition, that is, in the advanced stages of the disease.
He cited devastating data: &quot;Nine out of ten patients come when they already have some kind of opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to diagnose at an earlier stage, and therefore it is necessary to provide samples for detection in on a massive scale, for all the people who ask for it.&quot;
Experts and officials of the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco (COESIDA), as well as patients themselves, like Fabrizio, who turned to a private laboratory for testing, prompted only by the fact that his friend did it and, despite his at a young age, he was already at the stage of AIDS and even suffered from Kaposi&#39;s sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the most common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they&#39;re going to die and don&#39;t want to know anything.
&quot;Since I&#39;m going to die anyway, I&#39;d rather get drunk three times a week,&quot; they say. But not in my case.
There are positive changes, I eat well, I do exercises, I take medicines.
To date, his parents only know that he survived cancer.
I live a normal life like anyone else.
&quot;I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but with mutual responsibility, I take care of myself and the other person,&quot; listed Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO to move his statement to those who now, in the context of World AIDS Day, is experiencing fear.
Let them get tested if there was a risk of infection, let them know as soon as possible if they are HIV positive, that&#39;s better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them know that they can live like any other person, being responsible.
This message of his summarizes the theme of the fight against AIDS this year 2012.
condoms behind the counter
There are big gaps between health programs and the common citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has covered the HIV issue.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In the places devoted to this task, &quot;in fact, the distribution of condoms has increased, before we were given one or two, now we are given packets of a hundred, which is very good, but it turns out that there are those who now still do not have access to condom,&quot; he said.
Adolescents are among the most vulnerable to new infections.
&quot;Why do you need them?&quot; it is a popular question, with sniping and condemnation, from social workers, school counselors, pharmacists and health workers, that teenagers do not want to hear, the propagandist assured.
I propose to change this inefficient distribution; that condoms are not only behind the counters and that a hundred of them are in vending machines in public toilets in places frequented by young people.
This is not an encouragement for promiscuity.
It&#39;s not about paying for a beer and a motel, Gov. Emilio Gonzalez responded when asked if condoms could be handed out under his leadership.
&quot;It&#39;s not sexuality, it&#39;s best to make condoms available to those who are already sexually active,&quot; he said.
Key data in Jalisco
There were 13,435 total cases registered (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state is ranked 4th nationally for new and cumulative AIDS cases and 13th for HIV.
92% of infections are related to the sexual route, 6% through the blood and 2% to the perinatal route.
It is estimated that 50,000 people may be living with HIV, as for one reported case there are 4 to 5 people who do not know about it.
