Actor Larry Hagman dies
Larry Hagman, born September 21, 1931 in Fort Worth, Texas, became world famous for his starring role as John Ross Ewing, better known as &quot;JR&quot;, in the television series Dallas, in which he embodied a businessman without principles. , evil and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil tycoon JR Ewing on the television series Dallas became a symbol of greed in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as JR for the new season of Dallas, died Friday night of complications from cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., the Dallas production studio.
&quot;Larry is back in his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again playing the iconic role he loved most,&quot; his family said.
Larry&#39;s family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving Day Fair.
Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original series and the sequel, was by Hagman&#39;s side when he died in a Dallas hospital, spokesman Geoffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, affectionate and talented and I will miss him very much.
&quot;He had an original personality and lived life to the fullest,&quot; Gray confirmed in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and admitted to drinking for years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in his liver and underwent a transplant.
Long before &quot;Dallas,&quot; Hagman rose to prominence on television for his role as a decent type in the light comedy &quot;I Dream of Jeannie,&quot; which aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
In it, he played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive genie, played by Barbara Eden, and begins living under the same roof with her.
He was also the lead character in two rarely seen comedies, The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His film work has included critically acclaimed roles in The Group, Harry and Tonto and Primary Colors.
But it was his masterful interpretation of the delightfully obnoxious JR that catapulted Hagman to stardom.
A CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its entourage aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The advertising slogan &quot;Who shot JR?&quot;, conceived to create buzz around an emotional episode in which Hagman&#39;s character is almost killed, generated international discussion and millions of dollars risked in bookmakers.
It also helped bring the series to record-breaking audiences at the time.
When answered on the November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million viewers watched it, making Dallas the second most watched entertainment program in history, behind the 1983 MASH finale, which drew 50 million viewers.
It was JR&#39;s sister-in-law, Christine (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
JR got in her way and then threatened her that he would accuse her of prostitution if she didn&#39;t get out of town, but the others also had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing as a greedy, corrupt man with a charismatic smile: a dishonest businessman and unfaithful husband who wanted his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be put into treatment.
&quot;I know what should be on JR&#39;s tombstone,&quot; Hagman said in 1988.
It should say, &quot;Here lies honest citizen JR Ewing.&quot;
This is the only deal he lost.
Victoria Principal, also a heroine of the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone &quot;huge, both on and off the screen.&quot;
He is unforgettable and indispensable for millions of admirers around the world, and in the hearts of each of us who were lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of &quot;Dallas&quot; aired a few months ago to great acclaim on TNT.
The recording of five episodes of the second season had already been completed and a sixth was in production, the channel said.
Warner or TNT have not yet made a statement about what will happen to the series after Hagman&#39;s departure.
