A course that explores &quot;The End of the World&quot; begins
Each week, students explore apocalyptic phenomena such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
This semester, when religion professor Stuart Sharma decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew he had an irresistible lure: the end of the Mayan calendar&#39;s &quot;long countdown&quot; on December 21, which many people seized on as proof that the end of the world was coming. .
But Sharma had no idea what was in store for him in the next couple of months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, the financial crisis that some call &quot;long Armageddon&quot;, and the growing conflict that would drag Israel into the place where Christian end-time theorists believe the Apocalypse will begin.
&quot;I didn&#39;t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever,&quot; Sharma told students at Rutgers-Camden University in New Jersey this week.
If we analyze what is happening in the world at the present time, as if we had only 30 days left, it was a really good period.
And remember that bad is good for those who have an apocalyptic mindset.
And he&#39;s not the only professor to offer courses on &quot;the end of the world&quot; this semester, theoretically the last in history.
At Temple University, Associate Professor Barry Wacker teaches a course on Media, Culture and the End of the World.
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
&quot;We&#39;re analyzing why these ideas spread over time,&quot; he said, and the way in which hypothetical scenarios are proposed that cause certain human behaviors.
If nuclear material falls into the hands of terrorists, for example, war could break out.
