&quot;I tried to tell students about what is possible, likely, plausible and impossible,&quot; Wacker said.
On Pennsylvania State University&#39;s main campus, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an associate professor of art history and anthropology, teamed up to teach a course simply called &quot;The End of the World.&quot;
&quot;We&#39;re not adding &#39;2012&#39; so we can always read the course again if the world doesn&#39;t end,&quot; Restall said.
Despite the &quot;imminent destruction&quot;, students must study, prepare projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be taken on Apocalypse Eve, leaving students with no choice but to work &quot;until the night the world is supposed to end,&quot; Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
&quot;Seats filled out in two hours,&quot; Restall said of his high GPA course, which had 35 students enrolled.
We received emails for many weeks before the start of the semester from people asking if there were still places.
Students, in turn, assure that this course is one of the most interesting.
&quot;I love watching what people do to comfort themselves,&quot; said Brigid Robinson, a 23-year-old religion and sociology student from Haddonfield, New Jersey, in Rutgers Camden.
And the apocalyptic way of thinking, secular or religious, is only a matter of consolation or lack thereof.
Will Vekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he watched all the apocalyptic movies.
&quot;I&#39;ve never heard of a course that teaches this,&quot; he remarked.
I like him.
But none of the students interviewed - let alone the professor - said they believed in a December 21 date for the end of the world.
&quot;Our first project was about Mayan prophecy, and in a way we discredited it,&quot; said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior at Temple University from West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world; it&#39;s just a key moment on the calendar, Restall said.
But he noted that there is an apocalyptic uneasiness in Western culture that goes back several centuries, where people react to changes around them by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused an increase in these speculations.
&quot;In other places, people don&#39;t think about it,&quot; he said.
Predominantly in the English speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is teaching courses in the Philippines this year, quickly answered a question about whether he knew of any &quot;end of the world&quot; course there.
&quot;Philippines do not take part in the end of the world,&quot; he wrote, alluding to the order of a higher authority.
We have a pardon from the Pope.
Restall noted that many days of the final judgment had been spoken of for a long time, and said that if nothing happened on December 21st, &quot;people would immediately start thinking about the next date&quot; or philosophizing that December 21st was the start of a seven-year period after which the world will end.
Students and teachers are nonchalant about this date.
Some said they were going to go to &quot;doomsday&quot; parties.
&quot;Maybe I&#39;ll call some of my friends to laugh together,&quot; commented Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
